<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safety Authority Unveils Eurotunnel Fire Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The Anglo-French Channel Tunnel
Safety Authority Tuesday unveiled its highly critical report on
last November's Channel tunnel fire and ordered the operator
Eurotunnel to tighten up its safety procedures.
</P>
<P>
It said last year's fire "exposed fundamental weaknesses" in
Eurotunnel's safety management and made 36 recommendations for
improving safety in the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
However, the authority did not call for any changes in the
much-criticized semi-open design of the freight shuttle wagons
involved in the fire.
</P>
<P>
Eurotunnel has restricted its services and has shut down its
freight services altogether since November 18 last year when a big
fire broke out, which threatened the lives of three crew and 31
passengers and created tens of millions of pounds of damage.
</P>
<P>
The authority said that it must be satisfied that Eurotunnel
could rectify the faults before commercial service could resume at
its former level.
</P>
<P>
"Eurotunnel must, in particular, convince the Safety Authority
that it is possible to ensure the safe evacuation of passengers in
all circumstances," the authority added.
</P>
<P>
The go-ahead for resuming the freight shuttle service will
depend on the approval of the Anglo-French Intergovernmental
Commission which oversees the tunnel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
