<HEADLINE> France Welcomes Russia-NATO Partnership Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 14 (Xinhua) - France today hailed the deal between
Russia and NATO on forging a peaceful new relationship, describing
it as a "historical event".
</P>
<P>
"If this is confirmed, it would be a historic event because it
is an essential event in the definition of the new architecture of
European security, " Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques
Rummelhardt said.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking hours after a deal was reached in Moscow aimed
at placating Russia before the NATO western alliance invites new
members from former Soviet bloc countries in eastern Europe, a
move Russia has strongly opposed.
</P>
<P>
The pact, if approved by NATO governments and Russian President
Boris Yeltsin, will govern bilateral relations between the two
former Cold War foes after NATO's eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been bitterly opposed to the alliance's plans to
accept former Soviet bloc countries. The Czech Republic, Poland
and Hungary are expected to be invited to join the alliance this
summer.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was announced in Moscow today after two days of
tough negotiations between NATO Secretary General Javier Solana
and Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov. The two sides are
expected to sign the deal on May 27.
</P>
<P>
Rummelhardt said the agreement had been reached thanks to the
efforts of all the countries involved, particularly France and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
The accord has been under negotiation since January when French
President Jacques Chirac travelled to Moscow for talks with
Russian President Boris Yeltsin over the issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
Details of the agreement between Solana and Primakov were not
immediately released. 
</P>
</TEXT>
