<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-14 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Party Recognizes Palestinians' Right to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 14 (Xinhua) -- In an important move, Israel's
opposition Labor party decided today to include its recognition
of the Palestinians' right to self-determination into its
platform.
</P>
<P>
The decision was adopted with an overwhelming majority at
the Labor convention held at the Tel Aviv headquarters. Moreover,
the leftist party did not rule out the possibility of
establishing a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
But the party imposed some restrictions to the Palestinian
state, which should have no army and forge no alliance with
other countries, and Israel should retain full access to its
airspace.
</P>
<P>
The Labor's decision immediately came under harsh criticism
from the ruling rightist Likud party, which accused it of being
ready to hand over everything to the Palestinians. The Likud
also slammed the Labor for deserting its own principles by not
standing up to the Arab pressure.
</P>
<P>
Today's Labor convention opened following the one held
Tuesday night that rejected the bid by its current chairman Shimon
Peres to be appointed as party president. The objection was seen
as a victory for Ehud Barak, frontrunner for the Labor
leadership contest in the upcoming June 3 party elections.
</P>
<P>
It also signaled the end of the era of Peres, a veteran
politician and a leading architect of the Israeli-Arab peace
process. The countdown to Peres' era began a year ago when he
was defeated by Likud challenger Binyamin Netanyahu in last
May's general elections. Following the defeat, Peres announced
not to rerun for the leadership in the June elections.
</P>
<P>
Bidding to be appointed the party president, a newly
envisioned post by Peres' supporters, Peres hoped to continue
his active role within the party in order to finish his
unfulfilled task of realizing a comprehensive Israeli-Arab
peace.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, Barak, widely perceived as a hawk,
withdrew his earlier opposition to the acceptance of a
Palestinian state. He apparently tried to avoid further splitting
the party by making a concession to the dovish camp following
his victory in the Tuesday showdown with Peres.
</P>
<P>
Labor lawmaker Moshe Shahal, former public security minister,
hailed today's decision as a realistic and important move. He
said that "it's a change of attitude of a major Zionist party
in this country. And I think, more than anything else, this
decision is a realistic one."
</P>
<P>
Shahal refuted the claim that the latest move could further
erode Labor's image among the public, which threw it out of
power last May because of its soft stand toward the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He said such image was not right, and the Labor would do its
utmost to amend it. He justified the Labor's move to accept a
Palestinian state, saying even Netanyahu was talking about the
possibility of recognizing a Palestinian state with restricted
powers.
</P>
<P>
After the Barak-Peres showdown and today's party convention,
the Labor party is ready for the June 3 elections. In the wake
of last year's election defeat, the party has apparently
reorganized itself for a new role in the nation, which Barak has
defined as bringing down the Netanyahu government within one
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
