<HEADLINE> India Records Rare Photographs of Hale-Bopp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Indian scientists have taken
certain rare photographs of the Hale-Bopp comet which can shed new
light on astronomy, the Press Trust of India (PTI) said today.
</P>
<P>
A 14-member team of scientists from India's Positional
Astronomy Center (PAC) in West Bengal have been doing regular
observations of the comet's movement, still visible in the west
and northwest sky of the east Indian state.
</P>
<P>
PAC Director K. Chakraborty told PTI today that the
photographs, taken through sophisticated telescopes and other
electronic gadgets, might be placed before the international forum
of astronomers for future research work.
</P>
<P>
The observation program, which began on March 14, will continue
till May 31.
</P>
<P>
However, the PTI report failed to specify the characteristics
of the photographs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
