<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLO Official Attacks Israeli Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Farouk Kaddoumy, chairman of the PLO
Political Department, today lashed out at the Israeli government
for disrupting the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Kaddoumy, who arrived here today on a several-day visit to
Egypt, will have talks with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
on the possibility of resuming the Palestinian-Israeli
negotiations, which was deadlocked again in March when Israel
broke ground for a new Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem,
captured by the Jewish state in 1967.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival, Kaddoumy warned in a statement that Israel's
practices are "closing all doors of hopes," and threatening to
bring the region back to a whirlpool of violence.
</P>
<P>
"Israel does not really want peace," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"It was apparent, before and after the Oslo agreement, that
Israel did not wish to abide by the signed agreements and
categorically refused to hand over power to the Palestinians,"
said the PLO official.
</P>
<P>
"All that Israel wants is to give the Palestinians some powers
in the final phase and does not want to withdraw from the
occupied Arab territories," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has rejected a
proposal by Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu to speed up
the final talks on permanent peace for fear that Israel is
trying to avoid fulfilling its obligations in the interim
accords.
</P>
<P>
While the PNA conditioned the resumption of talks on freezing
Jewish settlement buildings, Israel insists on the Palestinian
cooperation in security.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Faisal al-Husseini, PNA minister for Jerusalem
affairs, said Israel must halt all measures to Judaize the holy
city before the peace talks can resume.
</P>
<P>
"Restoration of the negotiations hinges on stopping Israeli
settlement activities in Jerusalem," said Husseini, who is here
to attend an international conference on the Jerusalem issue
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"This settlement policy runs contrary to the
Palestinian-Israeli signed agreements and the international
legitimacy resolutions, he told an Egyptian TV.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to rebuild confidence between both sides,
U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis Ross today met with top
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat to pave way for the first
meeting between the Palestinians and Israelis in two months of
peace crisis.
</P>
<P>
No progress has been made since Ross renewed his shuttle
diplomacy to the region last week, the second in a month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
