<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Launches Cross-border Military Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish security forces
launched cross-border military operations against members of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), who are based in northern
Iraq, the Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official agency said that the security forces entered
northern Iraq early this morning and surrounded a large group of
PKK militants who shelter themselves in the regions of Sivi and
Dutaza.
</P>
<P>
The traffic to Habur Border Gate between Turkey and northern
Iraq was closed Tuesday night for the cross-border operations,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
Sermet Atacanli, deputy spokesman of the Turkish Foreign
Ministry told reporters today that "the Turkish troops provided
air and artillery support," following a call for aid by Iraq's
Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) Chairman Mesud Barzani. "And some
of our troops entered the region (northern Iraq) from Habur-Zaho
direction," he added.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli underlined that Turkey launched the operations with
limited forces, saying that necessary security measures had been
taken in order to prevent possible incursions from the
Turkish-Iraqi border.
</P>
<P>
"Our troops in the region may interfere in the clashes
between Barzani and the PKK when it is necessary," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Turkish private Show TV reported this evening that
about 50,000-strong Turkish troops had crossed the border into
northern Iraq in a bid to wipe out the PKK rebels whose
headquarters are in the area.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Turkish security forces today killed 30 PKK
militants and captured 32 others in Sirnak province, Eruh town
of Siirt province and Bitlis province, according to a statement
issued by the office of the Emergency Regional Rule.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that six PKK rebels surrendered to the
security forces in different provinces in the region.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting for autonomy in a nearly 13-year-old
separatist war, which has claimed over 21,000 lives in easter
and southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
