<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Carrier to Make Air Alliance with Overseas Carriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Airlines of the United
States will join hands with four other overseas carriers with a
view to stitching their operations and marketing efforts,
according to a report of the New York Times today.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation agreement, which is expected to be announced
Wednesday, includes Lufthansa, Air Canada, Thai Airways
International and Scandinavian Airlines System. The agreement will
require all the partners to share ticket offices and airport
operations, as well as jointly purchase supplies.
</P>
<P>
Although alliances between airlines are hardly new, the
agreement by the five carriers represents a new level of
cooperation and coordination. Industry experts predicted that ten
such groupings of airlines is likely to dominate the business in
10 or 15 years.
</P>
<P>
While the member airlines will maintain their current separate
identities, they will share a new logo and the theme line "The
Airline Network for Earth" to help market the alliance, called
Star Alliance.
</P>
<P>
By combining route networks, they can offer seamless service
between far-flung destination, experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
