<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MALE, the Maldives, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) today ended its first
summit after celebrating the 10th anniversary of its founding in
1995, determined to accelerate regional cooperation and implement
result-oriented plans.
</P>
<P>
Launched into business 11 and a half years ago with the
objectives of boosting economic development and eradicating
poverty in the region in a fast changing world, SAARC has now
become more business-like.
</P>
<P>
"A 10-year-old child is becoming a little more mature," Naeem
Hasan, secretary-general of SAARC, told Xinhua in an interview
before the three-day summit began on May 12.
</P>
<P>
"The trend in SAARC now is for a more action-oriented program.
In the first 10 years of SAARC's existence, we were talking in
general terms and now we are going into specific areas, specific
activities," Hasan said.
</P>
<P>
At the Male summit, the SAARC leaders came up with a more
ambitious plan, for creating a free trade zone -- the South Asian
Free Trade Area (SAFTA) -- by the year 2001, four years ahead of a
previous deadline.
</P>
<P>
At their last summit in New Delhi two years ago, they decided
to establish such a zone preferably by 2000 and not later than
2005. SAARC launched the South Asian Preferential Trading
Arrangement (SAPTA) in December 1995, marking its first step
toward the creation of a free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
SAARC leaders insist that 2001 is a "realistic target year."
This may reveal some measure of urgency or even confidence in
their eagerness to catch up with other regional groupings such as
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
SAARC leaders "resolved to accelerate regional cooperation in
order to realize the aims and objectives of the association," said
a declaration issued at the end of the summit.
</P>
<P>
Fully aware of its huge human resources and determined to wipe
out the scourge of poverty which is standing in the way of
development in the region of 1.2 billion people, the leaders
regard regional cooperation as "indispensable in an interdependent
world for the realization of the full potential of the South Asian
region."
</P>
<P>
SAARC was formed in December 1985 by seven countries --
Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri
Lanka -- with the main aim of promoting economic growth, social
progress and cultural development through joint action in agreed
areas of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past decade SAARC has matured as an institution and
the scope and volume of cooperative activities have expanded," the
declaration said.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to continued cooperation in agreed areas, SAARC
has now moved into the core areas of economic cooperation," it
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC leaders not only made the landmark decision to move
faster toward trade liberalization in the region by advancing the
deadline for the realization of the free trade zone. They also
decided to set up a group composed of eminent persons to conduct a
comprehensive review of SAARC after nearly 12 years of its
existence and identify measures to "further vitalize and enhance
the effectiveness of the association in achieving its objectives."
</P>
<P>
The leaders also agreed to enhance political cooperation. "The
aims of promoting peace, stability and amity and accelerated
socio-economic cooperation may be achieved by fostering
good-neighborly relations, relieving tensions and building
confidence...," they said. "A process of informal political
consultations would prove useful in this regard."
</P>
<P>
They reiterated their commitment to eradicating poverty in the
region by the year 2002 preferably and called for social
mobilization as part of this endeavor.
</P>
<P>
They also voiced deep concern over the plight of women and
children in the poverty-ridden region and adopted specific
measures to cope with the worsening environment.
</P>
<P>
Nobody can underestimate the potential of such a new-born force
which is increasingly attracting world attention, some observers
here said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
