<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 50th World Health Assembly Closes with Budget Adopted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The 50th World Health Assembly
closed here today with the adoption of a working program budget of
842.7 million U.S. dollars for 1998-1999.
</P>
<P>
The budget for 1998-1999 consists of six appropriation
sections: governing bodies, health policy and management, health
services development, promotion and protection of health,
integrated control of diseases and administrative services.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Assembly, highest governing body of the World
Health Organization (WHO), also adopted a budget-related
resolution. It requests the WHO director-general to present to the
101st session of the Executive Board in January 1998 an efficiency
plan that will enable WHO to save up to three percent from
administrative costs and overheads. The savings will then go to
priority health problems to which representatives of 191 WHO
members have agreed that a maximum amount of funds should be
allocated.
</P>
<P>
Representatives will gather again in Geneva in May next year
for a milestone session in the history of WHO. High on the agenda
are WHO's 50th anniversary, adoption of the global health policy
for the 21st century, and election of a director-general. Current
Director-General Dr Hiroshi Nakajima has announced that he will
not seek a third term when his second five-year tenure expires in
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
