<HEADLINE> Iraq Denounces Turkish Military Invasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today strongly denounced a
fresh Turkish military invasion of northern Iraq, demanding an
immediate withdrawal of Turkish troops, the Iraqi news agency
(INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the INA, an Iraqi foreign ministry spokesman
said that some Turkish troops invaded northern Iraq at 3:00 local
time Tuesday (23:00 GMT Monday).
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that the invasion violates the Iraqi
sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
He described such an act as contradictory to the U.N. charter
and principles of international laws as well as good neighborly
relations between Iraq and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The unidentified spokesman added that the Turkish intrusion
also ran counter with what Turkey talks about its commitment to
standards of good neighborliness. Iraq utterly rejects all the
pretexts given by Turkey to justify its invasion, he added.
</P>
<P>
Chasing Kurdish rebels does not authorize Turkey to encroach
upon the Iraqi territory and sovereignty, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He strongly demanded "an immediate and complete withdrawal" of
all the invading Turkish troops from the Iraqi territory.
</P>
<P>
He elaborated that two Turkish armored units supported by
helicopters intruded the Iraqi territory. One headed for the area
of Zakho while the other made its way to an area around
Amadiya. Both Zakho and Amadiya are border cities in the
northwest of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The INA quoted the spokesman as saying that the Turkish
invasion resulted in heavy losses of life and property of
Iraqi Kurds. No details were reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
