<HEADLINE> European Shares Mixed, Paris Hits New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Europe's major stock markets ended
mixed Wednesday, with the recent record-breaking rallies in both
London and Frankfurt losing momentum while Paris surging sharply
and hitting a new record closing high.
</P>
<P>
After an unprecedented 8-consecutive-session run of record
closing highs, British shares on the London market finally calmed
down and ended slightly lower for the first time in the past 12
session since the May 1 general election.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that share prices recovered from session lows as
Wall Street responded to US interest rate optimism after a subdued
set of US producer prices figures made a near-term interest rate
rise less likely.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index finished 4.1 points lower at 4,686.9.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt also ended their recent rally and
finished weaker as a continuing poor performance from Deutsche
Telekom weighed heavily on market sentiment. The DAX-30 share
index closed the session down 21.46 points, or 0.6 percent, at
3,573.69.
</P>
<P>
However, in Paris, French shares hit record highs on the back
of Dow movements and hopes that the ruling center-right coalition
will win power again which removed uncertainty about the oncoming
elections, with the CAC-40 index ending 55.05 points higher at
2,774.63.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index ended down 4.1 points at 4,686.9. The
Frankfurt DAX-30 index finished 21.46 points lower at 3,573.69.
The Paris CAC-40 index closed 55.05 points higher at 2,774.63.
</P>
</TEXT>
