<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Turkish Announcement on War Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has welcomed Turkish Prime
Minister Mecmetin Erbakan's announcement of the postponement of the
joint U.S.-Israel-Turkey military manoeuvres.
</P>
<P>
"This is the right decision if one takes into account the
climate which we would like to create and similar gestures
made by other parties," Government Spokesman Manolis Christofides
told reporters at his daily press briefing today.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan told reporters Tuesday that "the maneuvers are
postponed to coming years." But the Turkish military denied that
and there is no official confirmation from the Israeli or the
U.S. side.
</P>
<P>
The plan for the joint exercises was reported last week and
rejected by the Cypriot government, which called on the U.S. and
Israel to abide by international law.
</P>
<P>
A number of countries have voiced their concern over Turkey's
warming relations with Israel, saying the planned war games pose
threat their their security. 
