<HEADLINE> UK's Queen Outlines Legislative Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Britain's head of state Elizabeth
announced a legislative program today which includes 26 bills that
the government hopes to enact over the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
The package of bills covers a wide range of issues, with the
five major commitments of Labor Party in its election manifesto as
the centerpiece -- education, national health service, swifter
punishment of young offenders, more employment for young people
and better life for the whole country.
</P>
<P>
In her speech at an ages-old ceremony in the upper House of
Lords, Elizabeth said the education of young people was the
government's first priority.
</P>
<P>
The government "will work to raise standards in schools,
colleges and universities and to promote lifelong learning at the
workplace," she said.
</P>
<P>
In one of the two education bills, the government said to cut
class sizes by using money saved as a result of legislation
phasing out the assisted places scheme.
</P>
<P>
The other aims to raise school standards, develop a new role
for the local education authorities and parents and propose
reforms to the teaching profession.
</P>
<P>
On economy, Elizabeth said the central objectives "are high and
stable levels of economic growth and employment, to be achieved by
ensuring opportunity for all.
</P>
<P>
To that end, the government will introduce a bill to give the
Bank of England operational responsibility for setting interest
rates, in order to deliver price stability and support the
government's overall economic policy.
</P>
<P>
The government also pledged to build a new partnership with
business to "build a modern and dynamic economy to improve the
competitiveness" of Britain's industry.
</P>
<P>
As promised in the election campaign, the new Labor government
will mount a fundamental attack upon youth and long-term
unemployment and will take early steps to bring 250,000 young
people into work, financed by a levy on the excess profits of the
privatized utilities which will be brought forward in an early
budget.
</P>
<P>
On the Northern Ireland issue, Elizabeth said the new
government will "seek reconciliation and a political settlement
which has broad support, working in cooperation with the Irish
government."
</P>
<P>
On relationship with the European Union, the new government has
shifted the old passive stance and vowed to take a leading role.
</P>
<P>
"They will seek to promote employment, improve competitiveness,
complete the Single Market and opt into the Social Chapter," the
Queen said, adding the government will also work for the early and
successful enlargement of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
On the upcoming transfer of Hong Kong to China on June 30, the
Queen said her government will work to achieve a successful
transition.
</P>
<P>
The Queen's speech signals the formal opening of the parliament
elected on May 1. The Labor Party, after 18 years in opposition,
won 419 seats in the 659-seat lower house and came to power with
its leader Tony Blair as Britain's new prime minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
