<HEADLINE> ''Critical'' Agenda Prepared for OAU Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 14 (Xinhua) -- A critical agenda to review the
past and chart the course for Africa's future politics and
economics has been prepared for the 33rd Organisation of African
Unity (OAU) summit to be held here next month.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference today, Zimbabwean Foreign
Minister Stan Mudenge said the three-day assembly of African
heads of state and government starting on June 2 would discuss a
wide range of issues covering politics, economics and health.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''Pan-Africanism has triumphed, we have triumphed on
the political front and now we are on the economic war front.''
</P>
<P>
He added, ''all this takes place against political
developments of the Great Lakes, which will preoccupy the heads
and we will look at Liberia, Sierra Leone, Somalia, Burundi, the
peace process in Angola, the Middle East and the disagreement
between Libya, France, Britain and America.''
</P>
<P>
The summit will look at the Lome Convention in light of the
green paper that has been prepared by the European Union on the
state of relations and trade with African, Carribean and Pacific
countries after the year 2000 when the convention expires.
</P>
<P>
''The World Health Organisation (WHO) is proposing the
adoption of a declaration to fight malaria,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaria has reemerged as a fatal disease as a strain resistant
to most first line drugs is being experienced by many countries.
''We look forward to a busy time,'' the minister said. enditem

