<HEADLINE> African Ministers to Discuss Trade in Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 14 (Xinhua) -- African ministers of industry meet in
Ghana on May 26-28 to discuss new approaches to ensure that
industries on the continent participate in the globalisation process.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in Harare today, United Nations
Industrial Development Organisation (UNIDO) Country Director for
Botswana, Namibia, Zambia and Zimbabwe Niels Biering said the meeting
comes amid concern that there was need for new approaches from both
African governments and the international community to ensure that no
past policy failures were repeated.
</P>
<P>
About 35 to 40 ministers of industries or their deputies are
expected to attend the conference, organised by the UNIDO in
collaboration with the Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) and
the Organisation of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
Biering mentioned the prolonged protection of local industries and
the misguided donor belief that aid alone could lead to significant
economic transformation, particularly in Africa, reportedly to be the
world's poorest continent.
</P>
<P>
He said the cushion of aid had resulted in African governments not
taking full responsibility for their own development goals.
</P>
<P>
The pivotal role of the private sector was not given full reign to
develop, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the investment issue, he said that of the world's total
direct foreign investment flows, only five percent went to africa
and one percent to the 33 African least developed countries.
