<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Under-Secretary General Visits Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 14 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Under-Secretary General for
Political Affairs Kieran Prendergast arrived here today for
meetings with community leaders involved in the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival Prendergast reiterated that
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan will take a firm and final
decision toward the end of May on whether to invite the leaders of
the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities to direct talks.
</P>
<P>
Prendergast said he has "some questions and some ideas" to work
with during his meetings with President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the U.N. has been engaged in the process of
intensive dialog with the objective of resuming the intercommunal
talks at the level of head of respective communities.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General will take a final decision on this
after I get back and report to him, but I believe that the
expectation, subject to that decision, is that the talks should
resume by the middle of the year," he said.
</P>
<P>
After his meetings in Cyprus, Prendergast will visit Athens
and Ankara to discuss the Cyprus problem with officials there.
</P>
<P>
Replying to questions, he said talks are unlikely to take place
during next month's U.N. conference on the environment, which
Cypriot President Clerides will attend, because Annan would be too
preoccupied with conference proceedings and senior statesmen in
New York.
</P>
<P>
"He wants to start the talks and chair them at the beginning
and be available during them," the U.N. official added.
</P>
<P>
Prendergast will meet Clerides Thursday, and then he will go to
the Turkish-controlled northern part of Nicosia to have a meeting
with Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Prendergast's visit came at a time when the U.N.-led proximity
talks have entered the third month, during which the U.N. Resident
Representative Gustave Feissel had separate meetings with
Clerides and Denktash to prepare the ground for the face-to-face
negotiations between the two communities on the island.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when
the island was divided after the Turkish troops took control
of its northern third in the wake of a short-lived coup
seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
