<HEADLINE> Norwegian FM Calls for Halt of Har Homa Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The visiting Norwegian Foreign
Minister, Bjorn Godal, today called on Israel to freeze the
construction of the new Jewish settlement at Har Homa in East
Jerusalem, reported the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Godal, who is now on a Middle East peace mission, issued the
call when he was speaking to reporters after meeting with his
Israeli counterpart David Levy. He said: "The problem is more
important than other issues and it rests with Israel. I have a
firm opinion on that."
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian minister said that Norway has been critical of
Israel's settlement policy because it is a very sensitive
area. He added that it is true that the settlement policy cannot
be read as contrary to the wording of the Oslo Accords, but it
can easily been seen by the Palestinian side as anticipating the
stalemate of the negotiations and that is why it creates a
climate with difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Godal, who came here after talks in Egypt, Jordan and Syria,
indicated that he did not bring with him any specific proposals,
but only wanted to help create a favorable atmosphere for the
resumption of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Levy responded by asking how long the freeze of the Har Homa
construction would be expected to last. He said that if Israel
knew the specific timeframe, it would know what proposals to
consider.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on tonight's meeting between senior Israeli and
Palestinian officials in the presence of the U.S. Middle East
peace coordinator Dennis Ross at the U.S. Embassy in Tel Aviv,
Levy expressed hope that the objective is not just to hold one
meeting, but to clarify if it is possible to formulate an agenda
for both sides to make necessary effort to advance the peace
process. Levy declared that Israel wants to make progress.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was finalized after Ross met with Levy here and
Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat in Jericho. Israeli
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Palestinian Minister of
Planning and International Cooperation Nabil Sha'ath will attend
the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
