<HEADLINE> UNICEF Urges Donors to Quicken Food Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) today urged international donors to quicken their food
aid to the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
A UNICEF team, on its recent mission to Kangwon Province in the
southeast of the DPRK, found severe malnorishment among children
at nurseries, kindergartens, hospitals and at home.
</P>
<P>
The 40,000 plus kindergartens and nurseries in the DPRK have
been "running on empty" for months now, with little or no food,
Anthony Hewett, the mission chief, said at a press conference here
today. He complained that response from donors has been weak and
food aid is arriving far too slowly since UN agencies launched an
appeal to raise funds for aid to the DPRK in April.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF estimates that because of lack of food as few as 30 to
50 percent of children are attending nurseries or kindergartens,
where they would have been fed. The first priority is to pump
enough food into the system to get children back to nurseries,
kindergartens, and, where necessary, into hospitals, said Mr
Hewett, representative at UNICEF area office in Bangkok, Thailand.
</P>
<P>
As an immediate step, UNICEF plans to fly in a shipment of high
energy milk for malnourished children in Kangwon, and to begin
training hospital staff in therapeutic feeding techniques and
malnutrition-related health problems.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF warns that, until these institutions are back in full
operation, children's conditions will go worse. Flood damage and
the resulting destruction of industrial and social structures is
forcing the most vulnerable groups into "potentially lethal
nutritional decline", according to Hewett.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF is hoping for a stronger response from donors to the
crisis and meanwhile will continue to work in collaboration wi the
World Food Program (WFP), to help maintain the food supply to
nurseries, kindergartens and hospitals. It will also be supplying
antibiotics and hospital equipment in order to treat
hunger-related diseases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
