<HEADLINE> Waigel Confirms Intention to Sell Part of Deutsche </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 14 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
today confirmed the Bonn government's intention to sell off part
of its stake in the newly-privatized German telecom group,
Deutsche Telecom, to raise money to help offset an expected huge
budget shortfall for 1997.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue and step up the privatization," Waigel told
reporters in Bonn. "It is also conceivable that we will move up
the dates of steps in Telecom's privatization."
</P>
<P>
Deutsche Telecom, formerly a subsidiary of the federal post
office, went public six months ago. The government had promised
earlier that it would not dispose of any of the 75 percent Telecom
shares it still holds before the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
But pressure on the government to sell part of its Telecom
stake mounted in the past few days when it became quite clear that
the government would run up a huge financial shortfall for the
current year.
</P>
<P>
Waigel is scheduled to present the official tax estimates on
Thursday. According to speculations, the total government tax
deficits for 1997 could be 15 billion German marks (8.8 billion
U.S. dollars), or even 30 billion (17.6 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Apart from further privatization of Deutsche Telecom, the Bonn
government was also considering to cut spendings and to sell part
of the central bank's gold reserve, German media reported
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
