<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Inflation Further Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's month-on-month inflation
rose from 19.9 percent in March to 22.4 percent in April amid
warning that there will be no let-up to inflation during the rest
of the year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said today the central bank would not be able to meet
its inflation target of 21 percent by June due to what they said
"very serious" inflationary pressures in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Major threats to inflation included price rises and the
government'a bloated budget deficit, they said.
</P>
<P>
Among other items, food was again the major contributory
factor to high inflation in April, mainly due to high fruit and
vegetable prices as well as transport and medical costs.
</P>
<P>
Inflation is expected to exceed 25 percent by the end of June.
</P>
