<HEADLINE> Fourth Round of Northern Iraq Peace Talks Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The fourth round of northern Iraq
peace talks started here today to discuss measures for bringing
peace and stability to the region, the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of three rival parties, namely the Patriotic
Union of Kurdistan (PUK), the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) as
well as the Turkmen Front, and officials from the United States,
Britain and Turkey attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press before the talks, Turkish Foreign
Ministry Undersecretary Onur Oymen, head of the Turkish
delegation, said that the ceasefire provided in the region was a
success of the Ankara process.
</P>
<P>
The mechanism created to monitor the ceasefire was also
working well thanks to the efforts of all parties concerned,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources close to the talks were quoted as saying
that the fourth round of peace talks was a continuation of the
Ankara process, jointly sponsored by the U.S., Britain and
Turkey, but no concrete result could be expected.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came as the Turkish security troops launched a
massive cross-border military operation in pursuit of the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) early this morning.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement reached by the KDP and PUK in the third
round of peace talks last February, the Peace Monitoring Force
(PMF) began its mission in northern Iraq late last month to
supervise the truce between the two rival Kurdish parties in the
region.
</P>
<P>
A glimmer of hope was once expected when the PUK and KDP signed
a peace accord on October 31, 1996 under the mediation of the
U.S., Britain and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
However, The KDP's pullout from the peace talks cast a shadow
on the Ankara process after a high-ranking KDP official was
assassinated in northern Iraq in mid-March by alleged PUK
militants.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, supporting Iraq's Turkmen minority because of ethnic
and cultural bonds, wants the Turkmen to have a say in the
administration of the region.
</P>
<P>
The KDP, backed by the Iraqi government troops, fought
against the pro-Iran PUK and got the upper hand in late
August last year, leading to a U.S. air strike against the
Iraqi military targets.
</P>
<P>
The northern part of Iraq has been occupied by the two
Kurdish groups since the Gulf War in 1991, but it split into
rival zones after the KDP and PUK began fighting each in
1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
