<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls NATO-Russia Agreement "Historic Step" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today said the agreement reached between Russia and the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) was "a historic step" and
cleared the way to the signing of a NATO-Russia document.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the Rose Garden at the White House, Clinton said
the pact would give Russia "a voice in, but not a veto over NATO's
business."
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, NATO Secretary General Javier Solana and Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov reached the agreement after
two-day talks.
</P>
<P>
Details of the accord still remain unclear. But reports said
that the alliance and Russia agreed that they would sign a
so-called "Founding Act" document which would not need
ratification of parliaments.
</P>
<P>
Clinton told reporters that he was confident that the alliance
and Russia would approve the accord.
</P>
<P>
"Today's agreement sets out a sustained cooperative
relationship between NATO and Russia," he added. "NATO and Russia
will consult and coordinate regularly.
</P>
<P>
"Where they all agree, they will act jointly, as they are doing
today in Bosnia," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The 16 NATO members and Russia are expected to sign the
document on future relationship later this month in Paris just
before the alliance convenes its special summit on expansion in
July in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland are most likely to be
accepted by the alliance. "The first new members will not be the
last," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been opposing the expansion, insisting that it will
create new divide in Europe and threaten its security. Hence,
Russia asks NATO to guarantee that there will be no military
installations nor nuclear weapons in the new member states.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that there is an "explicit understanding" in the
agreement reached in Moscow that NATO will have to use some
infrastructure for the "agreed-upon operations that are an
integral part of being a NATO member."
</P>
<P>
"So all we're doing in the understanding is to recognize there
will be some use of military infrastructure so that the
requirements of membership can be met by any new members," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"But no, we are not moving the dividing line of Europe from
its old dividing line between NATO and the Warsaw Pact further
east," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
