<HEADLINE> Pentagon Confirms Russia Fires Laser at Canadian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 14 (Xinhua) -- A Russian cargo ship last month
fired a laser beam at a Canadian helicopter, injuring its pilot
and a U.S. Navy officer, the Pentagon confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Times reported today that the incident, which
occurred April 4 near Seattle, prompted a U.S. diplomatic protest
and the ship, Kapitan Man, was detained and searched by U.S.
officials.
</P>
<P>
Confirming the report but denying the lodging of any official
protest, Dick Bridges, a spokesman for the Pentagon, said that the
two men who were injured have recovered.
</P>
<P>
Their injuries were "consistent with damage caused by laser
burn" but the evidence is not conclusive, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The CH-124 helicopter was operating under a joint U.S.-Canadian
naval agreement when it was shot, according The Washington Times.
</P>
<P>
At the time of the incident, the Russian ship was sailing in
U.S. waters through the Strait of Juan De Fuca, north of
Washington's Puget Sound while the U.S. nuclear submarine USS Ohio
was going out the Strait.
</P>
<P>
The Russian ship's crew denied having any lasers aboard, but
the "top secret" Pentagon report said photographs taken by the
injured Navy officer showed a beam of red light being fired from
the ship.
</P>
<P>
The confrontation was "a stark reminder that cat-and-mouse
efforts to monitor strategic nuclear systems have not ended with
the Cold War," the U.S. newspaper reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
