<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The U.S. embassy in Jordan has declared to sponsor the
fifth annual U.S. product trade fair in Amman in an effort to
boost the U.S.-Jordanian trade exchange.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's exports to the U.S. in the past five years have been
stagnant at around 18 to 20 million U.S. dollars per year, while
the U.S. exported more than 350 million dollars of goods last year
to Jordan, according to sources at the U.S. Embassy here.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the U.S. and Jordan was not at the level that it
could be, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- About 55 million U.S. dollars was spent on 41 new
projects in the first quarter of this year, in comparison with 172
million dollars spent on 103 projects in the same period last
year, said Elias Farraj, assistant director-general at the
Investment Promotion Corp.
</P>
<P>
The decline can be attributed to the political uncertainty and
the figures are expected to increase once the political atmosphere
improves, he said.
</P>
<P>
The 41 projects are in five sectors that enjoy tax and customs
exemptions under an investment promotion law enacted a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The sectors are industry, agriculture, hotels, hospitals and
maritime and railway transportation.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- An international conference will be opened in London
soon to acquaint participants and investors with investment
opportunities in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Industry, Trade and Supply Minister Hani Mulki said that the
conference organized by a Swiss bank aims to familiarize
foreign investors with Jordan's financial and economic policies.
</P>
<P>
Investment is expected to flow into Jordan through the
conference, and in effect can boost the economic reform program,
the privatization process, the price-liberalizing process and the
country's efforts to join the World Trade organization.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The private sector is expected to shoulder nearly 70
percent of the investments in Egypt in the coming five years, the
Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
Total investments in the country would reach 400 billion
Egyptian pounds (about 117.6 billion U.S. dollars) during the 4th
five-year plan spanning 1997-2002, the paper quoted State Minister
of Planning Zafer al-Beshry as saying.
</P>
<P>
Private investors would provide 279 billion pounds (82 billion
dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics indicate that the private sector has
contributed 60 percent of the total investment in the past five
years, reaching 49.1 billion pounds (14.4 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The minister said the plan would open the door for the private
sectors to invest in the infrastructure field, such as power
stations, roads, airports and seaports, and the construction of
water plants.
</P>
<P>
The development strategy of the plan was mainly aimed at
raising the economic growth rate to an average 6.9 percent, which
would in turn achieve regular and continuous increase in the
national capital, he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has a population of more than 60 million with
unemployment rate reaching nearly 20 percent, according to a World
Bank report.
</P>
<P>
Investment is vital for creating jobs and Egypt plans to create
500,000-800,000 jobs each year by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
