<HEADLINE> Greek-Turkish Committees of Experts to Begin Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Greece confirmed today that the
Committees of Experts formed to review procedural matters relating
to differences between Greece and Turkey would begin operation by
exchanging views in writing.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said that the
process, with the exchange taking place via the Dutch EU
presidency, would enable each side to clearly set out its
positions.
</P>
<P>
"In this way, it will become clear whether there is common
ground," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that Athens was interested in
rapprochement and coming to an understanding with Ankara but only
within the framework of the three conditions set by Greece, namely
that Ankara must respect international law, international treaties
and acts in "a spirit of good faith."
</P>
<P>
The Greek-Turkish relations have been strained for decades over
territorial disputes and the Cyprus issue, but the recent months
have seen a thawing of the ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Athens and Ankara agreed last month to set up Committees of
Experts to examine their problems. Professor Krateros Ioannou and
professor Argyris Fatouros have been appointed by Athens as the
members of the Greek committee of experts while diplomat Sukru
Elegtag and jurist Suat Bilge will be the representatives of the
Turkish side.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Committees of Experts will prepare a
joint report by mid-june on processes proposed to resolve
Greek-Turkish problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
