<HEADLINE> Arab Parliamentarians Call for Peace, Solidarity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Leading Arab lawmakers today ended
their two-day meeting with a call to safeguard the Mideast peace
process and fortify Arab solidarity.
</P>
<P>
A communique, issued at the end of the 7th Arab Parliamentary
Union Conference this evening, stressed the Arab resolve to
realize a just and comprehensive peace, based on Israel's full
withdrawal from all occupied Arab territories.
</P>
<P>
The final communique asked Israel to make an unequivocal
commitment to completing the peace process on the basis of the
land-for-peace principle and relevant U.N. Security Council
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"Arab countries should freeze normalization with Israel until
it works for achieving a just and comprehensive peace," it said.
</P>
<P>
The document also recommended suspending Arab participation in
multilateral talks and "giving teeth to a first-degree Arab
boycott of Israel" until a just and comprehensive peace becomes a
reality.
</P>
<P>
The Mideast peace talks were plunged into a deadlock since
Israel broke ground in March for a new Jewish settlement in Arab
East Jerusalem, where Palestinians want as their future capital.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentary leaders from 18 Arab countries, emerging from
their final meeting at the Arab League headquarters here, also
stressed the importance of closing Arab ranks and establishing a
common market.
</P>
<P>
"Solidarity represents the general framework for cooperation
among Arab countries," said the parliamentarians, urging Arab
unity in face of the challenges posed by international changes
and developments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the communique said the achievement of economic
integrity through a common Arab market will help meet these
challenges.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the political role of the Arab Parliamentary Union
in setting up the Arab market, the communique said a
parliamentary committee composed of Egypt, Morocco, Syria,
Lebanon and Kuwait will follow up the implementation.
</P>
<P>
The conference also called for convening an Arab summit on a
regular basis with the purpose of drawing up a joint Arab policy
and solving inter-Arab differences within the framework of the
Arab League. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
