<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Warns Against Permanent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 14 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan said here
today Jordan will not be a substitute homeland for Palestinian
refugees and will not tolerate any attempt to undermine Jordan's
national unity.
</P>
<P>
He was rejecting the saying about a 700-million-U.S. dollar
plan designed by some American Jews, under which a large number of
Palestinian refugees will be permanently settled in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian king made the remarks when speaking to army
officers at the Hussein Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
Press reports here have said under the plan, each Palestinian
household to be settled in Jordan will get 30 thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
Jordan remains a strong supporter of the Palestinians in their
demand for the restoration of their rights on their own national
soil and there is no alternative to the Palestinians' choice, said
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The Central Intelligence Agency of the U.S. and the Israeli
intelligence bureau have noted that the money for the Palestinian
settlement plan comes from some Swiss banks, where the Jews have
deposited a big amount of money, published rumors said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Swiss government is ambiguous about
the plan but has not denied it.
</P>
<P>
Some 1 million Palestinians became homeless during the first
Middle East war in 1948 when Israel annexed part of the
Palestinian land. They are now in refugee camps in Jordan, Syria,
Lebanon and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
At present, Palestinians including the refugees comprise about
60 percent of Jordan's 4 million-strong population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
