<HEADLINE> France Urges Turkey to Withdraw Troops from Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 15 (Xinhua) -- France today urged Turkey to withdraw
its troops from northern Iraq as quickly as possible, and
expressed concern over the consequences of the Turkish
government's operation against the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK)
on ordinary people in the region.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt called on the
Turkish authorities to ensure that human rights were respected and
to ensure the civilian population was not affected by the fighting.
</P>
<P>
He also urged Turkey to stick to its statement made at the
launch of the operation on Wednesday that the action would end
soon.
</P>
<P>
France is worried that the Turkish intervention could
complicate the "fragile" situation in northern Iraq, Rummelhardt
said.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Turkish troops, backed by tanks and heavy
artillery, crossed the Turkish-Iraqi border on Wednesday in a
military operation against Kurdish separatist forces of the PKK
based in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkey claims that the PKK, which has bases and camps in
northern Iraq, has flourished near the Turkish border since Baghdad
lost control of the area following the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
More than 22,000 people have been killed in more than 12 years of
fighting between the Turkish army and the PKK, which is pursuing
an armed campaign for a Kurdish homeland in southeast Turkey.
</P>
