<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imported Tobacco Chokes Ukraine's Cigarette Makers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's cigarette production is
forecast to fall 12 percent this year, but not because Ukrainians
are smoking any less.
</P>
<P>
Foreign tobacco and cigarettes are flooding the Ukrainian
market, forcing domestic cigarette makers to cut production to
under 40 billion cigarettes in 1997, down 12 percent over the
previous year, said Olga Yurchenko, director of UkrTiutium, the
Ukrainian Association of Tobacco Manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Yurchenko complained that the Ukrainian government's measures
to stem the flow of cigarette imports has proved ineffective.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the government set minimum prices for tobacco
products and cracked down on cigarette smuggling to protect the
interests of domestic producers.
</P>
<P>
However, most Ukrainian cigarette producers use imported raw
materials.
</P>
<P>
Of the 45,000 tons of tobacco that went into making 45 billion
cigarettes in Ukraine last year, only 3,600 tons was
domestically produced.
</P>
<P>
UkrTiumtiun officials are lobbying the government to set
aside two percent of its tax revenues from the sale of cigarettes
to subsidize Ukraine's tobacco growers.
</P>
<P>
They say this will allow cigarette makers to increase the share
of Ukrainian tobacco in domestic cigarette production.
</P>
<P>
UkrTiutium is also concerned about the lack of quality control
over imported tobacco because the Ukrainian Customs doesn't have
the necessary equipment to ensure quality standards.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, analysts forecast that if Ukraine cancels tax breaks
for foreign enterprises, foreign investment in its tobacco
industry will slump dramatically.
</P>
<P>
The tobacco sector has attracted 130 million dollars in foreign
investment since 1992, accounting for about 10 percent of the
country's total foreign investment capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
