<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 15 (Xinhua) -- At least 30 villagers, most of them
women and children, were massacred Wednesday night in a farmstead
30 kilometers south of the Algerian capital Algiers, the
government said today.
</P>
<P>
The victims, among them two babies, 15 children and seven
women, were massacred by "a group of terrorists," a spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
But witnesses said that 36 people had their throats cut or were
shot dead in the massacre, which brought to 450 the number of
people killed by terrorists in their attacks upon villages and
bomb attacks in cities since April.
</P>
<P>
Five car bomb attacks which took place in Algiers on Sunday
killed between 11 and 16 people in the capital, Algerian
newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Algeria's political parties today kicked off their
campaign for the legislative elections scheduled for June 5.
</P>
<P>
Some 28 million Algerians will choose among 7,747 candidates for
parliamentary deputies to elect a new two-chamber parliament for
the country.
</P>
<P>
Troops will be deployed at polling stations during the vote,
and the 200,000 strong self-defense militia force will also be
called in to help provide security for voters, press reports
quoted Algerian officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian daily El Watan said that on Tuesday, the army
bombed an Islamic stronghold in the western region of Saida and
killed 11 Islamists. 
