<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinkel Says Moscow Has No Veto Over NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 15 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
today rejected Russian President Boris Yeltsin's view that
Wednesday's historic deal with NATO gave Russia a veto over NATO's
planned eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
"Russia will not take part in making the decision on who will
join NATO in the first wave," Kinkel told the German radio station
Deutschlandfunk.
</P>
<P>
He said that the draft accord on the future relationship
between Russia and the U.S.-led western military alliance was
wrongly interpreted by Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who
indicated Wednesday that Moscow would have a veto over NATO
expansion.
</P>
<P>
In a televised interview Wednesday night, Yeltsin said that
under the draft document to be signed by Russia and NATO countries
on May 27, NATO could "make decisions only after consensus is
reached through consultations (with Russia)".
</P>
<P>
NATO would make decisions on all issues concerning its future
on its own, Kinkel stressed. He said a joint cooperation council
would be created to deal with issues of common interest to NATO
and Russia, and in this council Russia will "of course have a say
understandably". But this clearly did not concern NATO expansion,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel made clear Germany was ready to sign the accord, agreed
on Wednesday by NATO Secretary General Javier Solana and Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov but not yet approved by the 16
NATO member governments.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, known as the NATO-Russia Founding Act, is
intended to formalize Russian input into European security
structures as NATO expands to include eastern European countries
which used to be Russia's allies in the Warsaw Pact.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said there was an agreement not to reveal the details of
the accord until 10 a.m. (0800 GMT) on Friday, and that he could
therefore not yet make any final judgment.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said the agreement, which is due to be signed at a
ceremony in Paris on May 27 by NATO members and Moscow, would form
the basis of a new European security structure in which Russia
would be included. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quebec Partition Likely After Separation, Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The majority of Canadians believe
that the province of Quebec will face partition if it separates
from Canada, according to a poll published today.
</P>
<P>
A Southam News/Compas poll found that up to 78 percent of
Canadians outside the French-speaking province anticipate it to
lose land as part of the price of independence.
</P>
<P>
In addition, about 50 percent of Quebecers agree that if Canada
is divisible, so is Quebec, according to the poll, which surveyed
2,450 people across the country from May 1 to 7.
</P>
<P>
The poll found that 92 percent of Canadians living outside
Quebec believe the province's Aboriginal people have the right to
stay with Canada in the event of a vote for independence.
</P>
<P>
This view is shared by an overwhelming 75 percent of Quebecers.
</P>
<P>
The poll results came as the Quebec issue moves to center stage
in the ongoing national election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Further, the results suggest that if Quebecers believe that
voting Yes would mean partition, they would be much less likely to
vote Yes.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of partition benefits the federalist side," said
Compas chairman Conrad Winn. "This may explain the sometimes
intense reaction of sovereignists to any discussion of the topic."
</P>
<P>
Before the 1995 referendum, the partition of Quebec was an idea
confined to only a few federalist pundits.
</P>
<P>
The narrow win of the No side by 50.6 percent of the vote made
many people to consider seriously what they would do if the Yes
side ever won a majority.
</P>
<P>
"It's the logical answer: if Canada is divisible, so is
Quebec," Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien noted shortly after
the referendum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
