<HEADLINE> Two Policemen Killed by Guerrillas in West Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Two policemen were killed today
in a western Nepali village by leftist guerrillas who have
launched a campaign boycotting the local elections scheduled for
Saturday, official sources here said.
</P>
<P>
A sub-inspector and a constable died on the spot when the armed
guerrillas hiding in a house in the village of Rukum District,
about 250 kilometers from Kathmandu, opened fire at a police
patrol team, an official from the district said.
</P>
<P>
Three other policemen were seriously wounded in the attack and
have been brought here by helicopter for treatment, he added.
</P>
<P>
The anti-election leftist guerrillas have recently increased
their activities in West Nepal's hilly areas in order to foil the
local elections.
</P>
<P>
Despite the government's special security arrangements like
deploying more police personnel in rural areas, the guerrillas
have successfully interrupted the electoral process in some remote
villages by spreading death threats among would-be candidates.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission last week decided to indefinitely
postpone the elections in about 40 villages of some western
districts as no nominations have been filed there under the
guerrillas' boycott campaign.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deputy Prime Minister Bamdev Gautum told reporters
here today that the local polls have been boycotted in 62
villages.
</P>
<P>
Many candidates in some remote villages who filed their
nominations earlier have reportedly been forced to withdraw their
candidacy under the guerrillas' pressure, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the deputy prime minister, who was from the
Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML), the
government has formed a task force to resolve the security crisis
in West Nepal by political means.  
</P>
</TEXT>
