<HEADLINE> France "Regrets" Cancellation of Mobutu-Kabila Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 15 (Xinhua) -- France today said it deeply regretted
the cancellation of a second meeting between Zairean President
Mobutu Sese Seko and rebel leader Laurent-Desire Kabila designed
to bring about peace in the war-torn African country.
</P>
<P>
"We are wondering about the motives put forward by Mr. Kabila
for refusing at the last minute to take part in this negotiation
and we wonder if the will to reach a peaceful solution in
resolving the Zairean crisis is equally shared by the two sides
(in Zaire)," French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt
said.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that the "unflagging efforts" made by South
African President Nelson Mandela to arrange a negotiated solution
to the Zairean crisis would finally lead to something.
</P>
<P>
Mandela called off planned talks on a South African navy
vessel in response to Kabila's last-minute demand Wednesday
evening that the talks be held in international waters and not in
Congo's port of Pointe Noire.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, whose forces now control three-quarters of the nation,
had insisted on talks at sea for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Rebels took up arms in October demanding Zairean nationality
for ethnic Tutsis and have made lightning advances across the
nation. They claimed their forces are nearing Kinshasa but the
government has dismissed such reports.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu, who suffers from cancer, agreed at peace talks on May 4
to hand power to an elected president but Kabila has insisted that
Mobutu hand over power at once to his Alliance of Democratic
Forces for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
