<HEADLINE> China Sets New Share Quota at 30 Billion Yuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- China plans to issue 30 billion
yuan-worth of new shares this year, the State Planning Commission
and the Securities Committee of the State Council jointly
announced today.
</P>
<P>
This move is aimed at giving better support to the national
economy and the large and medium-sized state enterprises, said the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of the new shares to be issued this year will
allow such enterprises to raise funds through stock placement and
prompt them to improve their management, which is expected to
result in a standardized development of the Chinese securities
market, according to the announcement.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the companies already on the waiting list to float
shares, the government will also encourage some of the listed
companies to issue more shares, said the announcement.
</P>
<P>
The probable candidates from the listed companies will be large
and medium-sized state firms having the support of the state's
industrial policy and a good profit-making record. They also need
to have a relatively small amount of listed shares, with the state
being the controlling stockholder, according to the announcement.
</P>
<P>
The announcement also urged related government departments at
all levels to be strict in selecting companies for listing.
</P>
</TEXT>
