<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Welcomes Russia-NATO Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 15 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today
welcomed Wednesday's agreement between Russia and NATO over their
future political and military relationship.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone conversation this morning with Russian President
Boris Yeltsin, the two leaders agreed that the pact, which had
been under negotiation since January, was a fundamental and
far-reaching step towards a durable guarantee of stability and
security in Europe, German government spokesman Peter Hausmann
said.
</P>
<P>
The document, which Hausmann said the German government had
contributed to negotiating, opened the perspective to a long-term
security partnership with Russia safeguarding the interests of
NATO (North Atlantic Treaty Organization) and its future new
members, as well as those of Russia.
</P>
<P>
Kohl also congratulated NATO Secretary General Javier Solana
and Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov on the successful
conclusion of the negotiations over the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The 16-page accord has been under negotiation since January and
will map out relations between Russia and the western military
alliance after its enlargement to take in former Soviet bloc
countries in central and eastern Europe, a move that Russia has
strongly opposed.
</P>
<P>
The deal was designed to ease Russian fears that NATO's planned
expansion to take in former Soviet bloc countries would threaten
its security and create new divisions in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The details of the accord, which includes the creation of a
NATO-Russia permanent council in Brussels, have to be approved by
NATO's 16 member governments and Russian President Boris Yeltsin
before leaders meet for a planned May 27 signing ceremony in
Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
