<HEADLINE> Review of Ethiopian Livestock Development Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Vice-Minister of
Agriculture Getachew Teklemedhin today called for a critical
review of the country's ''development path, research agenda and
policy environment with respect to livestock production''.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by the vice-minister when he was speaking at
the opening of the 5th National Conference of the Ethiopian Society
of Animal Production.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister stated that inspite of considerable investment
for the transfer of technology to ''resource-poor farmers'', there
has been little reward.
</P>
<P>
He urged conference participants ''to renew their effort and
work in various areas of research to assist the government in
designing and implementing development strategies and policies aimed
at the development of the livestock sub-sector''.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day confernece, 25 research papers on animal
production, animal feeds and nutrition will be presented.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has Africa's largest livestock population, with 33.8
million head of cattle, 43.9 million sheep and goats and about 5
million equine and camels. enditem

