<HEADLINE> Speech Contest Held to Greet HK's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- An English-language speech contest
held among college students to greet the return of Hong Kong to
the motherland ended here today.
</P>
<P>
Xu Yicheng, a contestant from the Beijing Foreign Studies
University, and Yuan Yuan, from the University of International
Business and Economics, shared the first prize in the contest.
</P>
<P>
With the topics of "An End and A Beginning" and "Red Buds Come
Into Full Bloom After A Hundred Years of Waiting", Xu and Yuan
greatly impressed the audience with their speeches.
</P>
<P>
The contestants all expressed their viewpoints on the history
of Hong Kong, the "one country, two systems" concept, the
procedure of Hong Kong's return and its significance, as well as
the prospects for the region.
</P>
<P>
After the contest Hu Wenzhong, a professor at Beijing Foreign
Studies University and chairman of the panel of judges, said he
had attended many English speech contests before, but none had the
significance as this one.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong is a topic that tapped the creativeness
and potentiality of all the contestants, he said.
</P>
<P>
Xia Qiang, deputy secretary of the Educational Work Commission
of the Beijing Municipal Committee of the Communist Party of
China, told Xinhua that the return of Hong Kong draws a lot of
attention among college students at present, and the universities
in Beijing have conducted many activities to review Hong Kong's
history and increase their understanding of the "one country, two
systems" concept.
</P>
<P>
Xia, also deputy director of the organizing body of the
contest, remarked that it had not only helped the students
understand history and improve their academic studies, but also
provided a chance to practice their speaking.
</P>
<P>
The contest was jointly sponsored by the Educational Work
Commission of the CPC Beijing Municipal Committee, the Beijing
Municipal Education Commission and the Beijing Television Station.
</P>
<P>
In the audience were Zhang Xiaowen, vice-minister in charge of
the State Education Commission, and Lu Yucheng, deputy mayor of
Beijing, as well as leading officials from relevant departments
including the Foreign Ministry and the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs
Office of the State Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
