<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Luxury, Extravagance to Be Rooted Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- A national teleconference
made a decision here today to focus on banning luxury
and extravagance in the campaign to fight corruption and
build a clean government this year.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jianxing, secretary of the Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection of the Chinese Communist Party, said that
president Jiang Zemin's important speech at the eighth plenary
session of the commission is of realistic and historic
significance for the anti-corruption campaign.
</P>
<P>
He said the Party's fine tradition of working hard ensures its
political superiority, and this spirit should be emphasized
more nowadays.
</P>
<P>
Because of the influence of the decadent ideas and life styles
of the bourgeoisie as well as of feudalism, some Party members and
cadres have forgotten this tradition, Wei explained.
</P>
<P>
In some places and units excessive consumption and extravagance
have run rampant, he said, adding that even some leaders have an
incorrect understanding of the issue, thus creating a hotbed for
corrupt activities.
</P>
<P>
He asked all departments and industries to focus on promoting
the tradition of hard work and thrift, and honestly implement the
rules and regulations banning luxury and extravagance.
</P>
<P>
He said that various kinds of excessive consumption and
extravagance appear in specific work areas. Therefore, professional
departments should improve management and strengthen financial
discipline to deal with the problem.
</P>
<P>
He called on the public, lawmakers, government advisors and the
media to supervise officials' activities.
</P>
<P>
Government leaders must take the lead in this regard, he said,
adding that leading officials of the Party committees and
the government must take personal charge of the work.  
</P>
</TEXT>
