<HEADLINE> EC Sends Aid to Former Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission today
approved a package of humanitarian aid worth 89 million ecus
(101 million U.S. dollars) for the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The aid, managed by the European Community Humanitarian
Office (ECHO), will enable UN specialist groups, the Red Cross and
non-governmental organisations to run programs until the end of
this year in the region, said the commission, the European Union's
executive body,
</P>
<P>
Apart from helping the fragile region recover from the near
four-year war in Bosnia, ECHO is also planning to speed up the
return of displaced persons and refugees through emergency repairs
to schools, health centers, houses and infrastructure, especially
electricity and water supplies.
</P>
<P>
ECHO said a total of 41 million ecus (48 million dollars) is
earmarked for programs in Bosnia and Herzegovina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
