<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislation Boosts China's Law Profession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- China's newly-published Lawyers'
Law has spurred the development of the lawyer profession since it
was adopted one year ago, according to Minister of Justice Xiao
Yang.
</P>
<P>
The number of lawyers surpassed 100,000 and that of law firms
totaled some 8,200 across the country at the end of last year,
Xiao told a forum held here today to mark the first anniversary of
the promulgation of the law.
</P>
<P>
The lawyers have handled more than 1.6 million lawsuits and
other legal business in the past year, as well as providing
services as legal consultants for 250,000 government agencies and
enterprises, Xiao said.
</P>
<P>
The law was adopted by the 19th Plenary Session of the Eighth
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, China's top
legislative body, on May 15 last year.
</P>
<P>
"The law was not only a milestone in the development of the
country's lawyer system, it also marked an advance in the course
of improving the socialist legal system," Xiao noted.
</P>
<P>
Jurisprudence has become a profession that is arousing popular
interest in China because lawyers are becoming increasingly
important in society, he said.
</P>
<P>
More than 120,000 people took national examinations to
qualify as lawyers last year.
</P>
<P>
Xiao urged lawyers to continuously improve their professional
levels and capability of handling lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
The forum was attended by Wang Guangying, vice-chairman of the
NPC Standing Committee, law experts and officials from the Supreme
People's Court, the Supreme People's Procuratorate, the Ministry
of Public Security and the Bureau of the Legislative Affairs under
the State Council.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
