<HEADLINE> Pakistan, India to Devise Mechanism for Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The foreign secretaries of
Pakistan and India, who will meet here in the next few weeks, will
"devise a mechanism to discuss bilateral issues in an integrated
and structured manner," Foreign Office spokesman Khalid Salim said
today.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions at a press conference here, Salim said
solution of all outstanding issues among the member states of the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) and
creation of a level playing field are the two essential elements
for exploiting the potential of the South Asia Free Trade Area.
</P>
<P>
He denied reports that Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
held talks with former Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabbani at the
extraordinary summit of the Economic Cooperation Organization
(ECO) held in Ashkhabad, the Turkmen capital, from Tuesday to
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Rabbani's regime is no longer the legitimate government of
Afghanistan," he said. "That's the reason the Afghan seat at the
Organization of the Islamic Conference summit here last March was
kept vacant."
</P>
<P>
When commenting on Uzbek President Islam Karimov's criticism of
Pakistan's support to the Taliban at the ECO summit, the spokesman
said, "We expressed our regrets that he made such a statement."
</P>
<P>
"We have been making serious efforts for an intra-Afghan
dialogue under the United Nations and the Organization of the
Islamic Conference in order to work for a broad-based and
acceptable government in the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
"To make allegations of this kind would only lead to the
vitiation of the atmosphere," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
