<HEADLINE> HK Approves Use of Hydraulic Hammers for Percussive Piling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Housing Authority's
Building Committee today approved the use of hydraulic hammers in
place of diesel ones for percussive piling work in four selected
piling contracts here.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the authority said here that the decision was
taken with a view to facilitating a smooth transition to the Noise
Control (Amendment) Bill, which is expected to become law soon
and is due to be effective from April next year.
</P>
<P>
Under this new legislation, the use of diesel hammers will be
gradually phased out over a period of two years.
</P>
<P>
The diesel hammer is the most common type of driving hammers
used for percussive piling in the trade of construction in Hong
Kong. But it is considered an environmental hazard for producing
much noise and emitting black smoke.
</P>
<P>
Hydraulic hammers, which are comparatively less noisy and
produce much less air pollution, are a practical substitute for
diesel ones.
</P>
<P>
It will be stipulated in the tender documents of the four
selected contracts, which will be tendered out between June and
August, that hydraulic hammers are required to be used for
installation of driven piles for one domestic block. Diesel
hammers can still be used for the rest of the piling works.
</P>
</TEXT>
