<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Changes Proposed to Two HK Ordinances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive's Office of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) today
published a revised package of amendments to the Public Order
Ordinance and the Societies Ordinance, noting that these changes
will be put before the legislators this weekend.
</P>
<P>
Michael Suen, secretary for policy coordination under the Chief
Executive Office, told a press conference that the revised
amendments to the two ordinances were made public after public
consultation and careful analysis of the views expressed.
</P>
<P>
"During the consultation, the public have expressed support for
the three fundamental principles underlying the proposed
amendments to the two ordinances," he said.
</P>
<P>
The three principles are "first, there has to be a proper
balance between civil liberties and social order; second, we must
uphold the Basic Law and the International Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights as they are applied to Hong Kong; and third, we
should guard against interference by foreign political forces in
local political activities."
</P>
<P>
He said, "We have listened carefully to public opinions on the
consultation document and have taken positive steps to address the
concerns expressed."
</P>
<P>
In early April, the office issued a consultation document to
solicit opinions and suggestions from the communities on its
proposals on the amendments to the two ordinances.
</P>
<P>
The proposals were made by the office in line with the
resolution of the Standing Committee of China's National People's
Congress that major amendments to the two ordinances introduced in
1992 and 1995 respectively shall not be adopted as the laws of the
HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Responding to reporters' questions, Suen said that a total of
11 amendments have been introduced to the original proposals. For
example, "national security" will be clearly defined in the law to
refer to "the safeguarding of the territorial integrity and the
independence of the People's Republic of China.'"
</P>
<P>
"The prohibition on foreign donations will now be restricted to
'direct or indirect financial contributions from foreign political
organizations' only with the removal of the references to 'aliens'
and 'foreign organizations'," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The financial contributions from political organizations in
Taiwan will be provided for separately in the law," Suen added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the proposals "only advocate the orderly
management and operation of societies," "aim at striking a proper
balance between civil liberties and social order," and "guard
against interference by foreign political forces in local
political activities."
</P>
<P>
"The Chief Executive and the HKSAR Executive Council are firmly
committed to safeguarding individual rights and freedoms which
Hong Kong currently enjoys," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
During the three-week consultation, the Chief Executive's
Office received a total of 5,507 written submissions, of which
4,744 are standard letters of one from or another, Suen said,
noting that groups and organizations accounted for 932 of the
submissions, and the remaining 4,575 submissions came from
individuals.
</P>
<P>
He said that these proposals are contained in the Societies
(Amendment) Bill 1997 and Public Order (Amendment) Bill 1997,
which will be introduced into the Provisional Legislative Council
on May 17, 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
