<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan May Cut its Foreign Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Japan may have to consider an
eventual reduction of its official development assistance (ODA)
while seeking other means to help developing countries, Japanese
Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda said today.
</P>
<P>
"Due to budgetary difficulties, the assistance can not be
expected to grow by leaps and bounds" as before, Ikeda told an
international conference on the future of Asia, held by Japan's
leading economic daily Nihon Keizai Shimbun.
</P>
<P>
Ikeda said that Japan would consider other sources of financial
flows other that government aid, like expanding market access for
goods from developing countries into Japan through deregulation or
obtaining special funds from the private sector.
</P>
<P>
A consultation body of the Japanese Foreign Ministry called
Tuesday for a reduction in Japan's financial aid and thorough
reform of its ODA program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
