<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Consumer Price Stable in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Canadian consumers paid 1.7 percent
more for the goods and services contained in the Consumer Price
Index (CPI) basket this April than the same period last year,
Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
Compared with April 1996, Canadian consumers paid more for new
vehicles and vehicle insurance, university tuition, clothing,
rental accommodation and meat.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, they paid less for mortgage loans, fresh
vegetables and soft drinks, the federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
April's 1.7 percent increase was lower than the annual rates of
2.0 to 2.2 percent seen in the previous months.
</P>
<P>
"The slowdown in overall inflation was related to smaller
movements in the transportation and food sectors," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Compared with March, the CPI registered no change in April.
Price increases for clothing and several other commodities offset
price declines for natural gas, gasoline and food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
