<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Village Autonomy in China Helps Rural Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Village autonomy has meant that, through competition, capable
persons who understand business management and do things properly
are elected as village cadres.
</P>
<P>
In the village of Fashi, Cai Qingquan, who is regarded as
knowledgeable, experienced, and clever, was chosen village
committee director through direct election in 1987 after retiring
from the army.
</P>
<P>
In April of this year, he was elected a fourth time. Since
then, he has been concerned about how to bring the villagers a
better life. He often discusses ways of improving the village
economy with other members of the village committee and village
representatives
</P>
<P>
The committee has got many people working in knitting,
clothing, and making resin handicrafts. It has also got villagers
to level three sand dunes to set up two tracts of land for living
quarters with an overall construction plan, build a new
kindergarten, and improve teaching facilities in the village
primary school.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the village has established an amusement center, a
library, and two parks.
</P>
<P>
In talking about the changes in the village over the past
years, the 73-year-old Cai betrays his deep feelings: "Only a
dozen years ago, my family used to eat sweet potato porridge twice
a day. Now we have rice every day, and we eat fish and meat often."
</P>
<P>
"We used oil lamps in the past, now there is electricity, and
many people have electric appliances in their homes. Most people
have telephones and they use gas for cooking. People go out on
motorcycles, or even in cars," the old man said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Village Autonomy in China Helps Rural Economy (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But still Cai is not satisfied. As soon as he was elected new
director of the village committee last month, he called together
members of the new village committee to discuss detailed plans for
helping the village economy.
</P>
<P>
This year's goal is for total industrial output in the village
of 120 million yuan -- and 200 million yuan by 1999.
</P>
<P>
The villages of coastal Fujian have not been the only ones to
benefit from village autonomy. Many villages in the inland areas
have also benefitted. Wuqiu Village in Hebei Province in north
China is a case in point.
</P>
<P>
It was in disarray for a long period of time. But, a village
committee elected directly by the villagers set about imparting
some order and looking for ways to get rid of the poverty. Village
cadres got the villagers to start businesses and plant fruit
trees. The village is now better off.
</P>
<P>
Lanzhou Village in northwest China's Gansu Province has no
more than 1,000 people. In recent years, the village committee has
been showing the advantage of village autonomy, and has got
villagers to start a dozen businesses, and more than 70 percent of
the village's work force are doing these businesses.
</P>
<P>
Lishu County in northeast China's Jilin Province is a national
model for autonomy. Its capable village cadres have found ways of
getting the average annual income of farmers up several hundred
yuan through raising pigs.
</P>
<P>
With the increased revenues, more than 120 million yuan has
been available for public affairs in the last several years.
</P>
<P>
"The achievements should be attributed to the implementation of
village autonomy," a deputy county magistrate was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
A Jilin provincial civil affairs official agrees to this,
saying, "With village autonomy and the people having their say in
major village affairs, everything can be done well." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Cargo Carrier to Open More Routes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' all-cargo
international flag carrier, Pacific East Asia Cargo (PEAC), is
planning to add more traffic rights to several international
airports.
</P>
<P>
PEAC Managing Director Benjamin Solis told reporters the PEAC
is eyeing Kuala Lumpur, Bangkok, Vietnam, Sydney, Macao and the
two Chinese cities of Xiamen and Shanghai to augment its present
five weekly freighter services to Hong Kong, Taipei, Seoul and
Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
"The PEAC will pursue traffic rights into China and continue to
develop strategic alliances and synergies with our colleagues in
the international air cargo industry," Solis said.
</P>
<P>
With regional deregulation in the offing, alliances would be
part of the PEAC's formula to minimize the effects of unbridled
competition, Solis added.
</P>
<P>
Solis said the PEAC's Asian network has a huge growth potential
and a solid foundation to become one of the region's major
all-cargo carriers soon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
