<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Condemns Turkish Incursion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Cairo-based Arab League (AL)
today condemned Turkish incursion into northern Iraq and warned of
its negative effect on Arab ties with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
A statement released by the AL Secretariat expressed deep
concern over Wednesday's operation when several thousand Turkish
troops, backed by tanks and heavy artillery, pushed across the
border into northern Iraq at dawn.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that such assaults might negatively affect joint
interests and deeply-rooted relations between the Arab states and
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"The use of military force to tackle reasons of tension in any
country would only aggravate the situation and jeopardize the
security of the area," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The organization called on the Turkish government to withdraw
its forces from the Iraqi territories.
</P>
<P>
These actions "run contrary to the principle of good
neighborhood, international law and conventions and represent an
interference in Iraq's domestic affairs," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
A Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman had rejected Iraq's
accusation that Wednesday's attack violated its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
He said the offensive was aimed at helping Kurdish Democratic
Party rebels in their fight against their rival, the Kurdistan
Workers Party (PKK) guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The PKK, fighting for control in northern Iraq and also for
autonomy in southeastern Turkey, uses bases in Iraq to launch
cross-border attacks on Turkish security troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
