<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The decision to extend membership in NATO to former
Soviet-bloc countries in Central Europe, which Russia explicitly
if grudgingly accepted Wednesday, is almost certainly the most
significant United States foreign policy initiative since the
end of the cold war.
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Tony Blair pledged his hyperactive Government
to an ambitious package of legislative promises Wednesday to bring
the changes to Britain he said were owed the country by his Labor
Party's overwhelming victory in the election.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Russia and NATO reached agreement Wednesday on a document
outlining a new political and military relationship that will
allow the alliance to expand to the former Soviet border.
</P>
<P>
-- Eagerly anticipated research results released Wednesday
indicate that two recently discovered breast cancer genes play a
less important role in cancer than scientists had presumed.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. government said that prices fell 0.6 percent at
the wholesale level in April, marking the fourth straight monthly
decline and the biggest drop in almost four years. 
</P>
