<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earth Gives Humans 33 Trillion-dollar Gift Every Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Earth gives humans 33 trillion
U.S. dollars worth of "goods" for free each year, nearly twice the
world's annual gross national product of 18 trillion dollars,
scientists and economists claimed in a journal published today.
</P>
<P>
The Earth's economic value to the world's people provided
by resources such as air, sea, rivers, mountains and food, falls
in the range of between 16 trillion and 54 trillion dollars a
year, with an average of 33 trillion dollars, the scientific team
reported in the journal Nature.
</P>
<P>
The scientists calculated the economic value of 17 ecosystem
services and broke their analysis down by biological sectors.
They say for example, that forests provide 141 dollars worth of
atmospheric gas regulation per hectare per year.
</P>
<P>
Forests also provide climate and disturbance regulation, water
regulation, nutrient cycling, waste treatment, food production,
raw materials, genetic resources, recreation and cultural
enjoyment to the tune of 969 dollars per hectare per year.
</P>
<P>
The study was carried out by Robert Costanza of the University
of Maryland and his colleagues. The figure was calculated using
recent published studies and some original calculations.
</P>
<P>
The numbers presented by the researchers are not meant to be
definitive -- their aim is to lay out the value of ecosystem
services in a form which would be useful for policy makers and the
public, and to stimulate debate.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said that the resources they have studied are
ignored by other economists, who consider only products that are
easier to value, such as man-made goods. The result is that these
major contributions to human welfare are not considered in
important political and economic decisions.
</P>
<P>
"What this study makes abundantly clear is that ecosystem
services provide an important portion of the total contribution to
human welfare on this planet," they said.
</P>
<P>
"If ecosystem services were actually paid for, in terms of
their value contribution to the global economy, the global price
system would be very different from what it is today," they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
