<HEADLINE> Village Autonomy In China Helps Rural Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The people of Chaole Village in
east China's province of Fujian had found themselves at a
crossroads in their lives: because of the sluggish fishing
business, they had to decide whether to go on with fishing or
to look for other businesses ashore.
</P>
<P>
So, more than 5,200 residents of this traditional fishing
village held a series of meetings to discuss the village's
future, and a consensus was reached: A village committee was
chosen directly by the villagers, and it in turn reached a
decision that Chaole should start on the development road by
starting businesses ashore.
</P>
<P>
By the early 1990s, the village had begun its rolling
development plan. It has spent two million yuan (24,000 US
dollars) establishing a "Chaole Industrial Zone", and now has 29
enterprises there. Its industrial output value reached 130
million yuan in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Standing on top of the village committee's office building,
Jing Jinding, the committee's director, showed reporters the new
houses several stories tall in the fishing village and remarked:
"Without the autonomy of the villagers, there would be no
democratic decision-making and democratic management, and the
development of Chaole Village would not be so fast and smooth."
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhenyao, a senior official with the Ministry of Civil
Affairs, who is in charge of building grass-roots political power,
says that in rural China, village autonomy is universal. "The
autonomy of villagers has become the direct force that is
bolstering the rural economy and safeguarding social stability in
the countryside," he adds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
