<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Steal Limelight at Pusan East Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese runners and swimmers
garnered 11 out of 26 gold medals on Thursday, breaking away from
South Korea in the medal tally at the second Pusan East Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
Of nine golds at stake in the first-day track and field
competitions, Japan edged China by 4-3 and Kazakhstan wound up with
the last two at the Kudok Stadium, while the swimmers of Japan made a
clean sweep of six gold medals in the pool.
</P>
<P>
However, China still retained its top spot with 35 golds against 26
of Japan and 13 for the host South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Nobuharu Asahara, 24, from Osaka of Japan, surpassed the Asian
record of 10.09 seconds by clocking in 10.04 under favourable winds of
4.0 meters per second.
</P>
<P>
"I was in my top form and the winds helped me run the fastest,"
said Nobuharu who had his personal best of 10.14 at the Atlanta
Olympic Games where he finished in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
Kiyonari Shibata of Japan outpaced Chinese Liu Lijun in the last
five meters to take the first athletics gold medal in the men's 1,500
meters in 3:49.90.
</P>
<P>
The other two gold medals for Japan were through Toshinari Takaoka
in the men's 10,000 meters and Masako Chiba in the women's 10,000
meters.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jianying won the first athletics gold medal for China by
clocking in 4:19.36 in the women's 1,500 meters, beating a duo of
Japanese to seond and third.
</P>
<P>
"I had paced the field from the very beginning and I deserved the
gold medal as my rivals were unable to outbeat me," said the
25-year-old Chinese woman who the personal best of 4:14.96 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Liang Yi took the women's 100 meters in her personal best
of 11.46 seconds, with teammate Yue Ling bagging home the bronze in
11.55. The silver medal went to Kaori Yoshida of Japan in 11.49.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Yanling and Luan Zhili, both of China, had a one-two finish in
the women's discus with 63.82 and 61.94 meters respectively.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan won two golds from the track and field through Alexandr
Korchagin in the men's pole vault and Elena Perchina in the women's
long jump.
</P>
<P>
Alexandr cleared 5.50 meters to claim the first place while
Perchina who had her personal best of 6.83 in 1996, jumped to a
distance of 6.59 meters to claim the women's long jump title.
</P>
<P>
The swimming finals ushered in all-Japanese champions in six
finals, leaving only three silvers left for China and Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
"We were delighted to make a clean sweep of the gold medals from
the day's finals, it will help us keep the second over-all place at
the East Asian Games," said Aoki Tsuyoshi, chief coach of the Japanese
swimming delegation.
</P>
<P>
Yasuko Tajima clocked 2:19.06 to take the women's 200m individual
medley, Sachiko Miyaji took the women's 800m freestyle title in
8:43.31, and a Japanese women quartet outpaced their Chinese peers in
the 4x100m medley relay to touch home first in 4:08.93.
</P>
<P>
Takashi Yamamoto took the men's 200m butterfly title in 1:58.01,
Keitaro Konnai swam the fastest in the men's 100m backstroke in 56.29,
and Tomohiro Yamanoi beat Kazakhstan's Alexei Khovrine to win the
men's 50m freestyle title in 23.36.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese divers displayed their prowess by finishing one-two in
the women's platform through Zhang Ying and Hu Wei. Zhang collected
501.42 points for the top honour while Hu Wei scored 492.87.
</P>
<P>
Of four judo gold medals, Chinese Sun Fuming took the women's over
72kg title, Yoshida Saki of Japan won the women's 72kg crown, and Kim
Min-soo of South Korea took the men's 95kg title with Shinohara
Shinichi of Japan taking the men's over 95kg finals.
</P>
<P>
Chinese weightlifter Yu Wenyu snatched a world record of 103kgs to
win the women's 70-kg category. Yu, 23, who started her weightfliting
career in 1990, said "I'm glad to win the gold medal with a world
record performance today after I even failed to make the National
Games."
</P>
<P>
Qing Guang notched up another gold medal for China by beating Chun
Yong Sung of South Korea in the men's 91-kg division with a combined
total of 365 kgs.
</P>
<P>
Huang Hsi Li of Chinese Taipei won the women's 76-kg category with
a total of 222.5 kgs while Kazakhstanian veteran Anatoly Khrapatty
took the men's 99-kg division with a games record weight of 395
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Japan bagged home two more golds in the men's over 95kg and women's
72kg judo competitions where China took the women's over 72kgs title
with the men's 95kg crown went to South Korea who also garnered both
the men's and women's team titles in the soft tennis tournaments.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Taipei outplayed Guam 92-66, Japan routed Mongolia 98-69
and South Korea edged Kazakhstan 70-69 in the men's basketball games,
while Chinese women cagers lost to South Korea 77-79.
</P>
<P>
The soccer fields featured a 7-0 victory for China over Guam, while
South Korea outscored Mongolia 4-0 and Japan tied Kazakhstan 2-2.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, 37 gold medals would be contested in athletics, judo,
soft tennis, swimming, weightlifting, wrestling and wushu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
