<HEADLINE> China, Australia Sign Memorandum on Hepatitis Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese and Australian
governments today signed a memorandum of understanding for a new
project aimed at improving China's ability to diagnose hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
The project will help the Beijing Biochemical and Immune
Reagents Center (BBIRC) upgrade equipment and train staff. The
BBIRC aims to become a reference center for hepatitis diagnosis
within two and a half years.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government will contribute about 1.3 million
Australian dollars (about one million US dollars) to finance the
project. Another 1.1 million yuan (about 132,000 US dollars) will
be provided by the Chinese government, according to the memorandum.
</P>
<P>
"The project will greatly improve the hepatitis diagnosis
capabilities of the Chinese hospitals and medical staff covered by
it," said Wang Xiaoke, director of the BBIRC.
</P>
<P>
Viral hepatitis is a major public health problem in China; it
has the highest incidence and mortality rates of all the
infectious diseases in the country.
</P>
<P>
There are at least 160 million hepatitis virus carriers among
China's 1.2 billion people at present, according to statistics
published by China's Ministry of Public Health this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
