<HEADLINE> China's April Tax Revenues Up Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial and commercial
tax revenues last month shot up 18.3 percent on a yearly basis,
according to the State Administration of Taxation (SAT) today.
</P>
<P>
Taxes collected by the central government were up 20.1 percent
and those going to local governments were up 16.3 percent in
April, the SAT said, without giving exact amounts.
</P>
<P>
The consumption tax and the value-added tax, two major parts of
China's tax reform of 1994, rose 12.7 percent last month on an
annual basis. The rate of increase was 4.5 percentage points lower
than for the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Personal income tax in April jumped 41.2 percent from a year
ago to 2.11 billion yuan while taxes from overseas-funded
enterprises and foreign companies reached 2.28 billion yuan, up
51.7 percent on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
Stamp taxes from securities trading reached 2.54 billion yuan
last month, 55 times the same month of last year.
</P>
<P>
In April, tax rebates on exports rose 16.7 percent to more than
3.5 billion yuan, for the largest monthly figure this year.
</P>
<P>
The SAT said that China's industrial and commercial taxes
between January and April were 17.7 percent more than a year ago
and 31.9 percent of this year's target.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
