<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK, Japan Sign Investment Protection Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Financial Secretary
Donald Tsang signed in Tokyo today on behalf of Hong Kong an
internationally binding Investment Promotion and Protection
Agreement (IPPA) with Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government was represented at the singing ceremony
by Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda, according to a Hong Kong
government announcement here.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, Tsang expressed his warm welcome to an
announcement by the Japanese government to accept the passport of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) as a valid
travel document and extend to SAR passport holders the same visa
privileges as those granted to holders of BN(O) passports.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the IPPA, the two governments will provide
equal treatment for investors, compensate any investments that may
be expropriated and permit free transfer of investments and
returns.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also provides for the settlement of investment
disputes in accordance with internationally accepted rules.
</P>
<P>
At present, Japan is the leading overseas investor in Hong
Kong. As of 1995, investment from Japan amounted to 191.4 billion
HK dollars (24.5 billion U.S. dollars) in total net asset at
original cost, representing 24.6 percent of the total foreign
investment in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's accumulated investment in Japan was 202 million HK
dollars (25.8 million U.S. dollars) in 1995, accounting for 0.7
percent of total foreign investment in Japan.
</P>
<P>
This is the 12th agreement that Hong Kong has signed in the
area of investment promotion and protection. Hong Kong has signed
similar accords with the Netherlands, Australia, Denmark, Sweden,
Switzerland, New Zealand, Italy, France, Germany, Belgium,
Luxembourg and Austria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Give the Disabled Equal Opportunities in Society (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- To many Chinese, disabled persons
are ofter referred to as "can fei", which literally means
"incomplete and useless". But 27-year-old Ding Tiejun would never
apply the tag to himself, although he has been a victim of severe
brain damage since the day he was born.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, the term "can fei" rather represents a
prejudice against disabled people, namely, only a healthy person
can be of use to society; a disabled person is someone to
pity rather than an equal participant in social life.
</P>
<P>
"This conception must be changed," emphasized Ding. The young
man, who has been confined to a wheelchair since childhood due to
cerebral palsy, firmly believes that "disabled persons are also
entitled to equal opportunities in society, and rehabilitation
helps them to overcome physiological and psychological obstacles
to regaining this right and realizing their value as human beings."
</P>
<P>
It was this belief that motivated Ding to establish in December
1992 the first community rehabilitation center for the disabled in
China run by a patient suffering from cerebral palsy. The
center, named "Aikang" or "health-loving", is in Ding's home in
northeast Beijing. Its staff consists of Ding and a score of
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
The young man called the establishment of the center "the first
step in my efforts to return to society and equally participate in
social life". He said that this makes him feel happy and
fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
This first step was made after years of efforts by himself and
his family to fight despair and seek a new horizon in life.
</P>
<P>
A mind is free to fly even though the body which contains it is
confined. "I loved to think about all kinds of things when I was a
little boy. What are the things in other people's minds? And what is
the world really like?" said Ding.
</P>
<P>
Refusing to idle his days away, little Ding began to learn
primary school courses from his elder sister. Later, he started to
read books on philosophy, logic, medicine and psychology. He even
gained a diploma in traditional Chinese medicine from a
correspondence school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Give the Disabled Equal Opportunities in Society (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Like most disabled persons, Ding had dreamed of becoming whole
after proper treatment, and endured terrible pain in the course of
treatment.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, he came to the newly established Boai Hospital, under
the China Rehabilitation Research Center, full of hope. However,
doctors there told him that he would never be able to stand up
again, although proper rehabilitation exercise could help restore
his disabilities to the maximum.
</P>
<P>
Ding recalled: "Although it was very, very agonizing to give up
my dream, but it jerked me out of illusions and forced me to
stand up to reality."
</P>
<P>
It was during that time that Ding learned the basic points of
the art of rehabilitation: Disabilities are not just damaged or
lost physiological or psychological functions. What is more
important, they alienate disabled people from the mainstream of
society. And the purpose of rehabilitation is to restore the
disabled to participation in social life.
</P>
<P>
Hoping to help fellow disabled persons with his knowledge of
medicine and psychology, and with the support of his family and
the local association for the disabled, Ding set up the Aikang
Community Rehabilitation Center.
</P>
<P>
Ding prefers to call those who seek his help recipients of his
service rather than patients. Over the past four years and a half,
Ding has helped hundreds of disabled people from all across China
with advice on medical treatment, rehabilitation and psychological
problems.
</P>
<P>
"The important thing is to encourage and help disabled persons
to stand on their own feet," Ding noted. He helped polio
patient Zhang Yan start her own business, and teenager Wang Lei,
who also suffers from cerebral palsy, get admitted to a
polytechnic school.
</P>
<P>
Because of his work, Ding became one of the five people in
China to win the Outstanding Disabled Persons Award from Rotary
International in 1994. And he was among the 120 outstanding
disabled persons commended at a national conference recently.
</P>
<P>
To Ding, the Aikang Center has become a bridge between himself
and society, and it is helping more and more disabled persons to
participate in normal social life.
</P>
<P>
Looking forward to the future, Ding said, the most important
thing for him to do is to "improve my ability to survive and
progress, and continue to do things that will benefit social
development." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
