<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Opposition Party Calls for Forming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 15 (Xinhua) - Jordan's largest centrist party has
responded positively to the largest opposition party's call to
form a coalition government that will uphold an anti-Israeli
policy and exert more efforts on domestic issues, Jordan Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We do not close door to anyone," said Hakim Kheir, Secretary
General for Information Affairs of the National Constitutional
Party (NCP), after the Islamic Action Front (IAF) Secretary
General Ishaq Farhan sent the message earlier this week, the
English newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
However, "the concept of a coalition government is very new
in Jordan and it is too early to talk about a coalition
government in which the NCP would participate with the IAF,"
kheir added.
</P>
<P>
The NCP was born from the merger of 9 centrist parties and
officially licensed by the Ministry of Interior earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the latest issue of Arabic weekly Al
Sabeel, Farhan said that "if the NCP agrees to form a coalition
government that would fight against normalization of ties with Israel,
prevent Zionist infiltration and place emphasis on issues of
domestic interests, we have no objection to becoming part of such
a coalition."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, discussions over the possibility of a
coalition government were underway between former prime minister
Abdul Karim Kabariti and some IAF personalities. But diverging
stands on normalizing ties with Israel and the economic
adjustment reforms prescribed by the International Monetary Fund
deadlocked the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has seen no coalition government in its history. The
current government is under the premiership of Abdul-Salam
Majali who was appointed in March by King Hussein of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
There has been 17 political parties licensed by the
government since a four-decade ban on political pluralism was
lifted in 1991 by King Hussein, the country's monarch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
