<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak to Face Revenue Shortfall of 1.25 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 15 (Xinhua) --Pakistan is expected to face a
revenue shortfall of 50 billion rupees (1.25 billion U.S. dollars)
in 1996-97 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
According to Deputy Chairman of the State Planning Commission
Hafiz Pasha, Pakistan is to realize 290 billion rupees (7.25
billion dollars) in revenue as against the target of 340 billion
rupees (8.5 billion dollars) for the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Pasha told the local media today, "Even we get the low revenue
collection in remaining two months, it was not likely to go below
the mark of 290 billion rupees."
</P>
<P>
Out of the total shortfall of 50 billion rupees, the government
of the Pakistan People's Party (PPP) shared a lion's share of 40
billion rupees while the remaining 10 billion rupees was prompted
by the recently introduced economic reforms packages for the
various sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tracing causes of the shortfall in revenues, Pasha said that
first of all the PPP government made an ambitious forecast of
revenue collection to the tune of 340 billion rupees for 1996-97
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The impact of economic reforms, recently announced, would range
between six to eight billion rupees, he estimated.
</P>
<P>
Pasha said that out of the total shortfall of 50 billion
rupees, the share of the present government is less than the
one-fourth due to drastic economic reforms, badly needed for the
surgery of the sagging economy.
</P>
<P>
However, he ruled out the possibility of drastic decline in
revenue collection beyond 290 billion rupees, "even if we get the
low revenue collection in remaining two months".
</P>
<P>
"It was this major shortfall in the revenue generation that was
leading us to the budget deficit," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pasha said, the previous government made adjustment in the tax
rate but it failed to make any headway in reforming the tax
collection machinery.
</P>
<P>
The government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif was introducing
measures to overhaul the tax collection machinery to ensure
maximum realization of revenues besides plugging loopholes that
prompted culture of tax evasion, said Pasha.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
