<HEADLINE> Chinese Lifter Sets World Record to Take Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese weightlifter Yu Wenyu set a new
world record in the snatch on her way to win the women's 70-kg
category at the second East Asian Games here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old girl from China's Liaoning Province snatched 103
kilograms, beating the previous world mark by 0.5 kilograms. The
lifted world record was set by China's Tang Weifang at the Hiroshima
Asian Games in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Yu Wenyu, who began her weightfliting career in 1990, met little
challenge from her rivals. After leading her nearest rival Kang Mi
Sook of South Korea in the snatch by 10 kilograms, the Chinese lifter
continued to dominate the clean and jerk, in which she had 122.5
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Yu Wenyu, who did not qualify for the finals of the National Games,
had a winning total of 225 kilograms for the crown. Kuo Su Fen of
Chinese Taipei was second 210 and Kang Mi Sook third at 207.5.
</P>
<P>
Yu Wenyu was pleased for the title. "I had been upset for my
failure in the qualifying competitions for the National Games," she
said. "But I am glad today."
</P>
<P>
Qing Guang notched up another gold medal for China in weightlifting
when he beat Chun Yong Sung of South Korea to win the men's 91-kg
division.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese lifter snatched 165 and jerked 200 kilograms from two
lifts.
</P>
<P>
Chun Yong Sung had the silver at 347.5 and Rafig Aliev of
Kazakhstan third at 335.
</P>
<P>
Huang Hsi Li of Chinese Taipei won the women's 76-kg category with
a combined weight of 222.5 kilograms from snatch at 97.5 and jerk at
125.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dong Hee of South Korea was second at 220 and Haseba Kumi of
Japan third at 202.5.
</P>
<P>
The only other gold in weightlifting on the day went to
Kazakhstanian veteran Anatoly Khrapatty, who won the men's 99-kg
division with a games record weight of 395 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
China's Tao Yueqiang was second at 375 and Choi Jong Keun of South
Korea third at 372.5.
</P>
<P>
The weightlifting tournament will conclude on Friday, with final
two divisions in the men's and women's sections respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
