<HEADLINE> Japanese Swimmers Make Clean Sweep at East Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese swimmers made big splashes
here on Thursday, sweeping all six gold medals at stake in the pool at
the second East Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
"We were delighted to make a clean sweep of the gold medals from
the day's finals, it will help us keep the second over-all place at
the East Asian Games," said Aoki Tsuyoshi, chief coach of the Japanese
swimming delegation.
</P>
<P>
Japan strode forth with three more silvers, leaving China with two
silvers and two bronzes. Kazakhstan returned with one silver, while
the hosts had only three bronzes and Chinese Taipei took the remaining
one bronze.
</P>
<P>
Yasuko Tajima clocked 2:19.06 to take the women's 200m individual
medley where Chinese Lu Bin settled for the second place in 2:20.35,
and South Korean Noh Joo-hee bagged home the bronze medal in 2:21.08.
</P>
<P>
The women's 800m freestyle title went to Sachiko Miyaji in 8:43.31,
teammate Reina Iwata finished second in 8:47.80, with Lin Chi-Chan of
Chinese Taipei won a lonely bronze medal in 8:51.11.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese women quartet outpaced their Chinese peers in the
4x100m medley relay to touch home first in 4:08.93, China ranked in a
distant second place in 4:13.55, and South Korea took the bronze medal
in 4:17.48.
</P>
<P>
Takashi Yamamoto took the men's 200m butterfly title in 1:58.01,
and Hisayoshi Tanaka helped Japan for a 1-2 finish by clocking 2:00.93
with the bronze medal taken by South Korean Kim Bang-hyun in 2:02.30.
</P>
<P>
The men's 100m backstroke crown was snatched by Keitaro Konnai in
56.29, teammate Hajime Itoi finished second in 57.09 and Chinese Fu
Yong secured a third-place finish in 57.13.
</P>
<P>
Tomohiro Yamanoi beat Kazakhstan's Alexei Khovrine to win the men's
50m freestyle title in 23.36. Alexei took the silver in 23.41 and
Chinese Zhang Xiao finished third in 23.75.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese divers displayed their prowess by finishing one-two in
the women's platform, beating South Korean Lee Mee-seon to third
place.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Ying collected a total of 501.42 points for the top honour,
Hu Wei came second in 492.87, and Korean Lee stood in a distant third
place in 460.32. 
</P>
