<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets With HK Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Vice-premier Qian Qichen, meeting
today with a delegation from Hong Kong's Guangdong Societies'
Committee led by its chairman Henry Fok Ying-tung, said he that is
delighted to note that the Guangdong societies are holding
various kinds of activities to celebrate the return of Hong Kong
to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's return to the motherland has been set, Qian said,
and people's confidence in it is increasing and there are good
conditions for a stable transition.
</P>
<P>
Despite the twists and turns during the transition period, he
said, on the whole, difficulties have been overcome. China's
political situation and society are stable, and the reforms and
opening to the outside world and economic construction have
continued to develop.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government will resolutely implement the "one
country, two systems" principle and the Hong Kong Basic Law, which
provides a guarantee for Hong Kong's smooth transition and long
stability and prosperity, Qian added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong's return to the motherland is a major
event not only for the Chinese nation, but also for the rest of
the world before the end of the century. The end of Britain's
colonial rule and the settlement of problems left over from
history by means of peaceful negotiations are of great historic
significance, he said.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed the belief that the Guangdong societies in Hong
Kong, together with other Hong Kong people, should be organized to
contribute to the celebration of Hong Kong's return and to a
stable transition.
</P>
<P>
He said it is his hope that the Guangdong societies in Hong
Kong will take the lead in supporting Chief Executive Tung Chee
Hwa of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) and the
work of the Hong Kong SAR government and the Provisional
Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
Qian said this means supporting "one country, two systems" and
"the Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong", and that: "We should
rely on the strength of the Hong Kong compatriots to maintain the
region's stability and prosperity."
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhaoguo, head of the United Front Work Department of the
Chinese Communist Party Central Committee, attended the
meeting. 
</P>
