<HEADLINE> Peace-keepers in Liberia Increase to 13,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 15 (Xinhua) -- With the last expected reinforcement
of west African soldiers arriving in Liberia this week, the
peace-keeping force there known as ECOMOG has now increased to
13,000, the "Nigerian Tribune" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the revised Abuja peace accord signed last August to end
the seven-year-old Liberian civil war, the ECOMOG was due to
increase its manpower from the then 8,500 to 13,000, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
In January, faced with a glaring deficit of troops, ECOMOG
Commander Victor Malu said he would need at least 12,500 men to
accomplish his mission.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG now comprises soldiers from 10 member countries of
the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS). Its top
mission now is to provide a secure environment for the
forthcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
In another development, leaders of the Liberian interim
government and its 16 political parties, as well as officials of
the independent electoral commission will meet today in Abuja to
decide a final date for the elections.
</P>
<P>
The revised Abuja peace accord has provided May 30 for the
parliamentary and presidential elections, but 11 Liberian parties
recently suggested that the elections be postponed to not early
than October 13, citing mainly the security situation as their
reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
