<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Villagers Take Action to Protect Wildlife (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Early this spring, a villager in a
remote mountain area, while cutting firewood near his house, found
a sick giant panda lying on the ground. He ran to a nearby
wildlife protection station some 30 km away and reported his
finding.
</P>
<P>
Several hours later, the giant panda was given emergency
treatment, and half a month later, it recovered and was sent back
to the woods.
</P>
<P>
The villager lives in the Sanguanmiao village in northwest
China's Shaanxi province. The village is located in the core area
of the Foping National Natural Reserve which is home to more than
60 giant pandas.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhan Jian, administration chief of the reserve,
during the past decade the reserve has cured 14 sick giant pandas,
most of them were first found and reported by local villagers.
</P>
<P>
"In our reserve such rare animals and birds like giant panda,
takin, and golden pheasant are often found appearing near
villagers' houses, and the villagers usually treat them very
friendly due to the raised awareness of wildlife protection," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that such awareness has been further spread after the
reserve was selected as one of the ten demonstration reserves in
China aided by the Global Environment Facility nearly two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
"Earlier this year we decided to confiscate the villagers'
hunting rifles so as to better protect the wildlife, after only a
little persuasion and education, all the rifles of the more than
300 villagers living within our reserve were soon handed over
without delay," Zhan said.
</P>
<P>
In the Shennongjia National Natural Reserve in Central China's
Hubei province, the Reserve Administration is also enjoying good
cooperation with the local villagers.
</P>
<P>
Zhan Quanyi, director of the Reserve Administration, said that
when heavy snow sealed the mountain area in recent years, the
local villagers were always mobilized by the government to do
something to help the wildlife.
</P>
<P>
"Usually villagers put some food on the main mountain passes
outside their villages," said the director.
</P>
<P>
He also said that sometimes some wild animals, driven by
hunger, came to villagers' pigsties for food. The villagers fed
them until the snow melted. "I remember one spring several years
ago, more than 100 muntjac were sent back to the mountains when
the heavy snow begun to thaw," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Villagers Take Action to Protect Wildlife (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In a town, it was said that five years ago there were still
people there selling specimens of wild animals and wild birds. But
in recent three years, these activities were never seen again.
</P>
<P>
The Xigou village, Honghua township in Shennongjia has 82
households and 321 villagers. On April 2 this year, the village
set up a 19-member Natural Resource Management Committee to help
the Reserve Administration in local wildlife protection.
</P>
<P>
"In the past it was the cadres that asked us to protect
wildlife, but now it is ourselves that want to protect the
wildlife for the good of our sons and grandsons," Mao Rizhao, head
of the village, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
According to an official from the Ministry of Forestry, China's
natural protecting campaign has been undertaken for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
"During the 40 years great efforts have been made, especially
to raise the public awareness of wildlife protection," said the
official.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the Ministry of Forestry,
cooperating with the Global Environment Facility, is now making
detailed plans to encourage more local participation and local
involvement in the protection of wildlife and their natural
habitats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
