<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets with US Federal Reserve Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin met with Alan
Greenspan, chairman of the Board of Governors of the US's Federal
Reserve System, in Beijing this afternoon, and described China's
macro-economic situation.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that in nearly three years of macro-economic
controls, the goal of curbing inflation has basically been
reached, and that the country's economic development has
maintained a relatively high growth rate and reforms of
state-owned enterprises are increasing. He predicted that in the
coming years, the good development trend will continue.
</P>
<P>
Jiang noted that the contacts between various kinds of people
from China and the US will help promote mutual understanding and
cooperation, and that he hopes Greenspan's visit will further
enhance the contacts and co-operation between the two countries'
financial sectors.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan said the economic reforms have brought about great
changes in China, which has scored rapid development in the financial
and securities markets in recent years.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief the market economy in China will enjoy
continuous development and improvement.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan also briefed Jiang on current economic and financial
developments in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the meeting were Dai Xianglong, governor of the
People's Bank of China, Chen Yuan, vice-governor of the bank, and
James Sasser, U.S. Ambassador to China.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan arrived here Wednesday morning for a three-day visit
as a guest of the Chinese central bank to study China's
macro-economic policy and to promote bilateral exchanges. 
</P>
