<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market closed
weaker today as a string of uninspiring bank profit results and a
bleaker earnings outlook for the sector.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished 5.4 points down at 2525.0,
after hitting a low of 2513.8 earlier.
</P>
<P>
"The banks really broke the market's back today," a
Melbourne-based trader said.
</P>
<P>
"There was a general lackluster tone across the board with the
banks taking most of the heat," he added.
</P>
<P>
Shares in the big four banks all fell as investors reassessed
the sector after recent record highs.
</P>
<P>
NAB Bank finished 23 cents down at 18.11 Australian dollars
after announcing an interim net profit of 1.139 billion Australian
dollars (877.03 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Warning from Managing Director Don Argus that the bank will
struggle to sustain record profit growth prompted a sell-off.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Bank shares closed 12.9 cents down at 7.321 Australian
dollars, Commonwealth Bank lost 13 cents to 14.65 Australian
dollars and ANZ ended 3.7 cents lower at 8.43 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index inched 1.6 points higher to close at
1429.9, while the all industrials dipped 13.7 points to 3949.3.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 303.27 million shares traded worth
822.97 million Australian dollars (633.68 million U.S. dollars),
with falls outnumbering rises by 569 to 454.  
</P>
</TEXT>
