<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Clone Cancer-Curbing Gene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Scientists in central China's
Hunan province have become the first in the world to clone the
entire sequence of the cancer-curbing gene Cx26 and complete an
analysis on the sequence.
</P>
<P>
The work by Professor Li Guiyuan and his colleagues in the
Hunan Medical University broadens the research of treating cancer,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have discovered that if cancer-suppressing genes in
the human body, which can maintain the stability of the internal
working environment for cells, become inactive, normal epithelial
cells tend to turn malignant.
</P>
<P>
The Cx26 is the second type of such genes discovered, which
play the role of communication between cells.
</P>
<P>
The scientists have confirmed that once the Cx26 loses
activity, meaning that it fails to recognize communication signals
between cells, the cells may turn malignant.
</P>
<P>
The Cx26 gene has not been discovered to lose sections or
mutate, as often happens to the first type of cancer-curbing
gene. As a result, the Cx26 is more suitable for use in gene
therapy of cancers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
