<HEADLINE> Japan Takes Lion's Share in First-Day Athletics Competitions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Japan bagged home four out of nine gold
medals at stake from the first-day track and field competitions,
stealing the limelight at the second Pusan East Asian Games here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
By outpacing Liu Lijun of China in the last five meters, Kiyonari
Shibata of Japan took the first athletics gold medal in the men's
1,500 meters, initiating its hunting for the gold medals at the Kudok
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
Kiyonari clocked in 3:49.90, Liu Lijun was kicked by Tomihiro
Umetsu of Japan in his left leg at the last ten meters to rank second
in 3:49.97, and South Korean Kim Soon-hyong finished third in 3:51.18.
</P>
<P>
Japan stood atop with three more silvers and four more bronzes
while China ranked second with three golds, five silvers and three
bronzes and Kazakhstan third with two golds. South Korea only bagged
home one silver and one bronze.
</P>
<P>
Nobuharu Asahara, 24, from Osaka of Japan, surpassed the Asian
record of 10.09 seconds set by Vitaliy Savin of Kazakhstan in 1995,
clocking in 10.04 under favourable winds conditions of 4.0 meters per
second.
</P>
<P>
"I was in my top form and the winds helped me to run the fastest,"
said the Japanese who had his personal best of 10.14 at the Atlanta
Olympic Games where he finished in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
Nobuharu won the men's 100-meter title, beating Lin Wei of China to
second in 10.30 while another Japanese Hideki Onohara finished third
in 10.36.
</P>
<P>
Nobuharu started his athletics career at the age of 18, was also
competiting in the long jump event in which he took the title in the
1993 East Asian Championships in Manila.
</P>
<P>
The other two gold medals for Japan were through Toshinari Takaoka
in the men's 10,000 meters and Masako Chiba in the women's 10,000
meters.
</P>
<P>
Toshinari clocked his winning mark of 28:44.60, with compatriot
Kenji Takao taking the silver in 29:29.08. Chinese Wang Zhicheng
finished third in the 10,000 meters in 29:49.54.
</P>
<P>
Masako took the women's title in 31:31.85, beating Chinese Wang
Mingxia to second in 32:47.20, with Yuko Kawakami awarding Japan
another bronze medal in 33:02.25.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jianying won the first athletics gold medal for China by
clocking in 4:19.36 in the women's 1,500 meters, beating a duo of
Japanese to seond and third. National champion Yoshiko Ichikawa
finished second in 4:19.80 and Minori Hayakari took the bronze in
4:21.37.
</P>
<P>
"I had paced the field from the very beginning and I deserved the
gold medal as my rivals were unable to outbeat me," said the
25-year-old Chinese woman who the personal best of 4:14.96 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"I have the powers to break away at early stage since I had been
training for the long-distance events," said Liu who ranked eighth in
the world in the 10,000 meters in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Liang Yi took the women's 100 meters in her personal best
of 11.46 seconds, with teammate Yue Ling bagging home the bronze in
11.55. The silver medal went to Kaori Yoshida of Japan in 11.49.
</P>
<P>
Liang Yi, from Nanjing of Jiangsu province, was recruited into the
Chinese delegation after clocking 11.55 at the National Champions
Championship in September last year.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Yanling of Luan Zhili, both of China, finished atop in the
women's discus with 63.82 and 61.94 meters respectively. Yuka
Murofushi of Japan took the bronze in a distant 51.90 meter.
</P>
<P>
"Even prior to the games, I was sure to win the gold medal," said
the 29-year-old Chinese veteran who returned to the circles after a
four-year break before the Atlanta Olympic Games where she finished
fifth in 65.10 meters.
</P>
<P>
The other two gold medals went to Kazakhstan's Alexandr Korchagin
in the men's pole vault and woman compatriot Elena Perchina in the
long jump event.
</P>
<P>
Alexandr cleared 5.50 meters to claim the first place, South Korean
Kim Chal-kyun finished second in 5.40 while Chinese Xu Gang took the
bronze medal, also in 5.40.
</P>
<P>
Perchina who had her personal best of 6.83 in 1996, jumped to a
distance of 6.59 meters to claim the women's long jump title, beating
Chinese Yu Yiqun and Zhang Hongling to second and third.
</P>
<P>
Yu finished in 6.42 meters and Zhang took the bronze in 6.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
