<HEADLINE> 300 Foreign State Leaders Visit Great Wall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The most popular section of China's
Great Wall near Beijing has been visited by 300 heads of state and
government of foreign countries since it received the Nepalese
prime minister in 1960.
</P>
<P>
President of Cote d'Ivoire Henri Konan Bedie was the 300th VIP
to Badaling Pass of the Great Wall during his stay in Beijing
early this month.
</P>
<P>
His name has joined the list with former US presidents Richard
Nixon and Ronald Reagan, former Japanese Prime Minister Kakuei
Tanaka, Queen Elizabeth II, and Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Known in China as "the 10,000-li wall", the Great Wall
stretches 6,700 kilometers. Constructed during the Warring States
period (475-221 B.C.), the Wall was completed during the Ming
Dynasty (1368-1644).
</P>
<P>
It is one of the few man-made architectural works that can be
seen by orbiting astronauts.
</P>
<P>
Late Chinese leader Chairman Mao Zedong's saying - "if you fail
to reach the Great Wall you are not a true man" - makes the wall
more well-known both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Constructed on rolling hills at Beijing's Yanqing County in
1505, Badaling Pass is considered as one of the best places to see
the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the Great Wall was listed in the book of world
heritage published by the United Nations Educational, Scientific
and Cultural Organization, and Badaling Pass received the honor as
the representative of the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that more than five million overseas tourists
came to Badaling in the past six years, including boxer Muhammad
Ali, soccer player Diego Maradona, and singer Luciano Pavarotti.
</P>
<P>
Local tourism authority has made huge investments in
construction of infrastructure and tourist facilities in the past
decade to offer better services.
</P>
<P>
An expressway linking Badaling and urban Beijing is under
construction and will be open to traffic this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
