<HEADLINE> Turkish Fighters Bombard PKK Camps in Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkish air forces today
bombarded the camps and bases of the outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK) in northern Iraq after the 50,000-strong Turkish
troops crossed the border into the region Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
F-4 fighters first took off from the air bases in
Diyarbakir and in Erhac of Malatya province of southeastern
Turkey at 05:30 a.m. local time (02:30 GMT) and bombarded the
PKK Sinat, Hakurk, Zap, Zeli, Hafta camps in northern Iraq.
Later, Turkish Cobra armed helicopters also bombarded the PKK
camps in the region.
</P>
<P>
Sermet Atacanli, deputy spokesman of the Turkish Foreign
Ministry said Wednesday that the Turkish government troops
launched the cross-border military operations following a call for
aid by Iraq's Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) Chairman Mesud
Barzani.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported today that
the PKK rebels in northern Iraq are escaping toward the
Iranian border following the bombardment of the Turkish fighters.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 PKK militants have been killed in Sarisavaklar
region of northern Iraq during the large-scale Turkish
cross-border military operations which started Wednesday morning,
said the agency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the agency added that the KDP forces seriously
clashed with the PKK guerrillas in Darkaracan and Begova regions
in northern Iraq Wednesday and the Turkish security forces
started to advance toward the two regions this morning.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a separatist war for autonomy in
southeastern Turkey since August 1984. Its armed wing, based in
northern Iraq, has been waging hit-and-run battles against the
government forces from across the borders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
