<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Controls More Share of Egypt's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The private sector now controls
nearly 40 percent of Egypt's annual 1.8-million-tonne sugar
market, up from less than 10 percent in 1990, according to the May
issue of Egypt's Business Monthly magazine.
</P>
<P>
This is the result of the government's privatization drive
which encouraged the private sectors to play a more active role in
the trade, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, private firms are now entirely responsible for
importing the 700,000 tonnes of sugar Egypt needs to make up for
its production deficit each year.
</P>
<P>
The government decided Sunday to sell 20 percent stake of the
shares of the Sugar and Integrated Industries Company (SIIC) at
the stock exchange, along with other giant public companies.
</P>
<P>
The sale of 7.6 million shares will make around 574 million
Egyptian pounds (169 million U.S. dollars), according to the
cabinet's Privatization Committee.
</P>
<P>
SIIC, an affiliate of the Food Industries Holding Co., has
controlled the sugar market ever since President Gamal Abdel
Nasser nationalized the holdings of sugar-magnate Abu Pasha.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the government's encouragement, a new private sugar
mill began operation in late March, two more mills will open later
and an existing private mill will double its capacity by 1998,
thus adding up to 500,000 tonnes of sugar a year in private
milling capacity, according to the monthly magazine.
</P>
<P>
Egypt needs to import about 100,000 tonnes of top quality sugar
a year to meet the demand of soft-drink makers and pharmaceutical
firms.
</P>
<P>
The new mills are expected to produce higher quality sugar to
help reduce the imports.
</P>
<P>
Sugar is considered Egypt's second most sensitive commodity
after wheat. Contrary to popular belief, Egyptians' sugar
consumption lags behind that of developed nations.
</P>
<P>
Egyptians consume 29 kilograms of sugar per person a year, much
less than the 37 kilograms of sugar per person for the
Europeans.
</P>
<P>
But still Egypt's sugar consumption will rise at a brisk 4
percent to 5 percent per year, much higher than the world annual
growth at 1.5 to 2.5 percent, the magazine said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
