<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Military Denies Postponement of Tripartite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking military official has
categorically rejected Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan's recent
statement on the postponement of the Turkish-Israeli-U.S. joint
naval exercises scheduled to be launched later this year.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today quoted this senior official
from the General Staff, who declined to be named, as saying that
the three-nation joint war games would be held later this year.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with visiting Iraqi Justice Minister Shabib
Al-Maliki on Tuesday, Erbakan said that the planned
Turkish-Israeli-U.S. military exercises had been postponed to
"some future year."
</P>
<P>
The military official said no change had been made about the
joint exercises, adding that Prime Minister Erbakan made his
statement without consulting with those involved in planning the
games.
</P>
<P>
Expressing his astonishment at such remarks, the official was
quoted by the Daily news as asking that "since when, up to now,
has the Prime Minister played a role in the decision-making
process in relations with Israel?"
</P>
<P>
The senior official told the paper that Erbakan just made this
inaccurate statement to appease those Arab nations which were
disturbed by the rapidly growing Turkish-Israeli cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The official's denial of the postponement of the war games
was later confirmed by both the foreign ministry and the defense
ministry.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a weekly press conference here, Foreign Ministry
Deputy Spokesman Sermet Atacanli said that no information about
the postponement of the joint military exercises was obtained from
the military sources.
</P>
<P>
Describing Erbakan's remarks as "a wrong conclusion," Defense
Minister Turhan Tayan, who paid an official visit to Israel
recently, said that postponing the maneuvers was "out of the
question and preparations for the exercises will continue."
</P>
<P>
The increasingly expanding Turkish-Israeli military cooperation
has caused grave disturbance among the Arab world, which accused
Turkey of trying to form an alliance with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
However, the Turkish side has rejected such an allegation,
saying that the Turkish-Israeli-U.S. joint military drills are
just a normal search-and-rescue operation in the Mediterranean
instead of a drill directed against the Arab nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
