<HEADLINE> Party's Fine Style of Hard Work, Thrift Urged to Carry Forward (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Jiang Zemin, general secretary of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and state
president, called for revival of the Party's fine tradition of
hard work and thrift in an effort to end indulgence in luxury and
extravagance.
</P>
<P>
He made the call in a speech on January 29 at the Eighth
Plenary Session of the CPC Central Commission for Discipline
Inspection. The summary of his speech, which is released here
today, is as follows:
</P>
<P>
"In the course of reform and opening-up and developing the
socialist market economy, for various reasons, the Party's fine
tradition and style of hard work and thrift have faded from the
memories of quite a number of Party members and officials," Jiang
said.
</P>
<P>
"It is almost in vogue in many regions, departments and units
to go in for pomp, extravagance and lavish spending," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Some people wallow in material comforts, luxury and
dissipation," he said, "and the situation is horrifying."
</P>
<P>
Jiang enumerated six such phenomena:
</P>
<P>
-- Some leading officials go regularly to expensive
entertainment places such as luxury hotels and night clubs,
spending money like water, Some officials even gamble and visit
prostitutes, using public funds to do so. Some of the so-called
"training centers", "sanatoriums" and "local government agencies
set up in Beijing" have actually become places for wining and
dining. It is very difficult to estimate how much money has thus
wasted every year.
</P>
</TEXT>
