<HEADLINE> Ingredient in Tea Said to Kill Cancer Cells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists in central
China's Hunan Province have found that catechol, or catechin, in
tea can lead to cancer cells committing "suicide".
</P>
<P>
Among three kinds of tea which have proved to be effective in
killing cancer cells, the non-fermented green tea takes the lead,
according to the results of an experiment conducted by a student
with master degree named Zhao Yan at Hunan Medical University.
</P>
<P>
The half-fermented oolong tea and wholely-fermented black tea
can also kill cancer cells, the experiment shows.
</P>
<P>
Zhao found through the experiments on 21 kinds of tea she had
collected from China, Japan and the Republic of Korea that the
tea's effect on the cancer cells depends on its type, growing area
and processing methods, such as whether it has been fermented or
not.
</P>
<P>
The amount of catechol in tea is also vital in deciding the
effect on cancer cells, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that this research finding has provided a new
theory for abstracting highly effective anti-cancer drugs with
little side-effects from natural plants.  Enitem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
