<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed lower
today as the U.S. dollar probed four-month lows against the
Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended at 77.66 U.S. cents, down from
77.84 previously.
</P>
<P>
The market was anticipating further clues from the central bank
on its thoughts on interest rate policy in light of remarks this
week by Prime Minister John Howard that the federal budget for
1997-1998 would probably not stand in the way of a rate cut, if
the Reserve Bank wanted to ease.
</P>
<P>
Later, the market lifted on remarks in federal parliament by
Deputy Prime Minister Tim Fischer, which were initially
interpreted as implying another rate cut was on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said: "Let me point out to the House that the interest
rate reductions which have occurred under the coalition government
have saved farmers over 300 million Australian dollars (210
million U.S. dollars) already, with more to come."
</P>
<P>
As the full report of Fischer's remarks were digested the
market retraced a little to end around its closing levels.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed lower at 90.29 against the
Japanese yen from 92.58.
</P>
<P>
Against the German mark, it was at 1.3152 from 1.3264.
</P>
</TEXT>
