<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to Develop 1st Private Hospital in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore Technologies
Industrial Corporation (STIC), a government-linked conglomerate,
has invested 11 million U.S. dollars in a maiden health-care joint
venture to develop a first private hospital and clinics in China,
the Business Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The mainboard-listed company's health-care vehicle is
Toronto-incorporated Inter-health Canada (China) Inc. (ICCI), in
which the STIC has taken a 50 percent stake, the report said,
adding that China will be STIC's initial health-care focus.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a company spokesman was quoted as saying that ICCI
has entered into a 51:49 joint venture agreement with two Chinese
partners, including state-owned enterprise Beijing Comprehensive
Investment Co., to set up Beijing Toronto International Hospital
(BTIH).
</P>
<P>
BTIH is going to be the company that will develop Beijing's
first private hospital and a network of eight clinics in key
cities including Shanghai, Tianjin and Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
These clinics will be linked to the new hospital through
various means, including information technology and telemedicine,
it said.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the 250-bed hospital is targeted at
the expatriate community of at least 200,000 people in Beijing as
well as high-income Chinese nationals.
</P>
<P>
The hospital, which is going to be located in the Beijing
Technological Development Area, will be built in three phases and
is expected to be completed at the end of year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
