<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Use Low Earth Orbit Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said today it will
consider using low earth orbit (LEO) satellite after the available
mass facilities of the Malaysia East Asia Satellite (Measat) are
fully utilized.
</P>
<P>
Energy, Telecommunications and Posts Minister Leo Moggie said
that in future LEO satellite may have its uses especially in
providing specific type of facilities which are not provided by
other satellite systems.
</P>
<P>
The LEO satellite, an example of a host of new
telecommunication systems and services, which would be emerging by
the end of this decade, would add a personal communication
capability allowing direct access from user terminals to
satellites, he said after opening the International Wireless and
Telecommunications Symposium (IWTS ' 97) at Shah Alam near here
today.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the success of his country's Multimedia Super
Corridor (MSC) would depend largely on the development of
telecommunications which he said forms the basic structure of the
whole endeavor.
</P>
<P>
He said that without wireless and telecommunications, there
would not be the MSC. MSC stretching southward from the Kuala
Lumpur city center is a 15 kilometer by 50 kilometer zone
specially designed for hi-tech development.
</P>
<P>
Two Malaysia-owned Measats were launched last year.
</P>
<P>
Participants from 35 countries and regions are attending the
three-day wireless and telecommunications symposium.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
