<HEADLINE> Malaysia to launch Volunteer Corps Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is to launch its own
volunteer corps program next month as part of government efforts
to revive volunteerism, Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The program, known as Yayasan Salam (Greeting Foundation), is
to garner the younger generation into using their respective
expertise to perform voluntary social services domestically and
abroad, Anwar said when launching this year's National Youth Day
Rally and Convention here.
</P>
<P>
National Youth Day is officially gazetted for observance in
Malaysia every May 15.
</P>
<P>
Volunteer teachers, doctors and engineers will be deployed to
the country's interior, requiring their expertise to raise the
quality of life of the community there, Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
He said that for overseas stints, the Malaysian government
planned to send Yayasan Salam volunteers for similar assignments
in poor countries in the region such as Laos and Cambodia and in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Yayasan Salam will testify to the willingness of our young men
to serve locally and abroad over a long period to do social
work," Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
According to the deputy prime minister, the program was among
proposals submitted to the Cabinet Committee on Social Problems of
which he is the chairman, and recently endorsed for
implementation.
</P>
<P>
The details of the Yayasan Salam program will be announced when
it is launched, Anwar said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
