<HEADLINE> S. Africa Threatens to Stall Trade Talks With EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has threatened
to stall trade negotiations with the European Union (EU) unless
it gets more favorable concessions on its agricultural exports,
local daily "The Citizen" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Parliament's trade and foreign affairs
committees in Cape Town on Wednesday, Trade and Industry
Ministry's Chief Director of Foreign Trade Relations, Faizel
Ismail, said South Africa was extremely concerned that 40 percent
of its trade with the EU that stood to benefit most from an
agreement on agriculture, had been excluded from a free trade
area.
</P>
<P>
Ismail revealed, Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin told
the EU's Director for Development Philippe Soubestre on Tuesday
that South Africa would be "seriously concerned" from going ahead
with the trade talks with any enthusiasm until it had a clear
indication of some real progress in reducing the long list of
agricultural exclusions.
</P>
<P>
He also said South Africa did not believe it had received a
satisfactory response to the issue of compensation for the
structural adjustments it would have to make before the
finalization of a free trade agreement with the EU.
</P>
<P>
The issue of the agricultural exclusions had been raised
several times in trade negotiations since the end of last year,
said Ismail, adding he hoped there would be a significant and
positive response by a planned inter-ministerial meeting went
ahead in July this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
