<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 08:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President: No Army Intervention in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
has asked the Turkish Armed Force not to intervene in the current
political tension in the country.
</P>
<P>
Demirel made the remarks on board his special plane on the way
home from Turkmenian capital Askhabad where he participated in the
Economic Cooperation Organization (ECO) summit, local newspaper
Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the reporters accompanying him, the Turkish
president said that he had told both Chief of General Staff Ismail
Hakki Karadayi and Islamic Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan that
the army must keep out of politics.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past three months, I made six speeches on TV and
tried to request from each and every one that no one should force
the military to defend itself," Demirel was quoted by the Daily
News as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We have twenty political parties. Let them discuss everything
among themselves." he added.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, political confrontation has been increasing
between the top commanders and Prime Minister Erbakan. The
military said the coalition government had became a protection
umbrella of the force which posed a serious threat to the
secularist system established by Mustafa Kemel, founder of the
Turkish Republic.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a rally was organized in Istanbul, the largest city of
Turkey, in protest against the military-proposed uninterrupted
compulsory eight-year education.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported that the General Staff had called a
emergency meeting to discuss the latest Istanbul mass rally,
which the military said had turned into an anti-secular
demonstration because the protesters claimed the compulsory
eight-year education could lead to the closing of religious
schools.
</P>
<P>
Justifying the meeting attended by top officers, President
Demirel said that people should not be disturbed by a routine
conference in which the generals were carrying out their duties
as defenders of the republic.
</P>
<P>
Clearly wary of the rising tension, Erbakan reiterated early
this week that Turkey's secularism and democracy brooked no
change, saying Turkey was a democratic country based on the
supremacy of law.
</P>
<P>
There have been rumors that Erbakan's Welfare Party-led
coalition government had been shaken under the pressure from both
the junior coalition, True Path Party and the military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
