<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Geographical Distribution of China's Listed Firms Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The geographical distribution of
Chinese companies listed on the stock market has seen considerable
change since 1996, analysts say, and is becoming more equitable as
more companies from less-developed areas go public.
</P>
<P>
More than 26 percent of the 603 companies listed on the
Shanghai and Shenzhen stock exchanges are from central and western
China, eight percentage points more than at the end of 1995. Of
272 companies listed between 1996 and the end of last month, about
36 percent were from the central and western parts of the
country. The percentage of companies from developed coastal areas
has fallen from nearly 80 percent to 65.4.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that changes in the geographical distribution
indicate that China's effort to transform enterprises into
joint-stock companies has been extending from the coastal areas to
interior areas, and this development trend is good for the
balanced growth of China's regional economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cost of Managing AIDS Victims to Soar in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 15 (Xinhua) -- At least one in every five people
living in urban centers in Kenya is a HIV/ AIDS victim and the
cost of caring for them could reach 207.4 million U.S. Dollars by
2010, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
There will be about one million AIDS sufferers by 2005 in the
eastern African country currently with a population of 28
million, according to the latest reports by several AIDS-related
local research bodies.
</P>
<P>
Now HIV/AIDS in-patients alone stand to consume 90 percent of
the available resources which would lead to a major economic
imbalance in Kenya, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The reports found out that both agricultural and business
sectors stood to suffer incurring huge expenses in treating
employees suffering from AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The National AIDS Control Program (NACP) and the Family Health
International (FHI) have identified 300,000 children who have
lost their mothers due to AIDS scourge, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The prevalence of HIV, the virus which causes AIDS, in capital
Nairobi and some other major cities in the country now lies
between 20 and 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
The reports called for measures adopted at the workplaces
around the country to stem the fatal disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
