<HEADLINE> World Bank Project Lauded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, May 15 (Xinhua) -- A World Bank-financed project to
develop the red soil of east China's Fujian Province was given
high marks by a bank evaluation team recently.
</P>
<P>
The project, which began in June of 1994, covers 80 river
valleys in four cities and 18 counties and involves 30 million US
dollars in loans. Fruit trees planted on 800 ha of land, as part
of the project, began bearing fruit this year.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale construction of water conservation facilities and
roads has greatly improved conditions within the project area and
has helped create 12,000 jobs for local farmers, a provincial
official said.
</P>
<P>
Among the economic benefits of the project in the past three
years have been an additional 9,000 tons of grain and an
additional 174 million yuan in output value, he said, adding that
many orchards were destroyed last year by a hurricane but those
within the project area were largely unaffected.  
</P>
