<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said here today his government is set on a right course
toward resolving outstanding issues with India through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"The initiation of dialogue with India is a good beginning
toward creating a conducive atmosphere for resolving outstanding
issues," Sharif told reporters here today.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his meeting with his Indian counterpart, I. K.
Gujral, Sharif said, "The meeting is a good step toward creating
atmosphere for dialogue in the face of tension and escalating
defense budgets between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
"The two countries need to change last 50 years stance as an
appraisal of policies will reveal that neither has gained anything
from the tension," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Pakistani prime minister said the meeting should
not be taken to mean that all issues will be settled in no time.
</P>
<P>
"I don't claim that all problems will be solved within 24
hours, it may take months and some years to resolve all the issues
with India," Sharif said while reiterating that Kashmir is the
core issue between Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question, he said, "I have seen in the meeting
that the Indian prime minister too desires to resolve the issues
through dialogue."
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that working groups on all outstanding issues
between the two countries will be formed at the end of next month.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
