<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accord on Solving Bangladesh's Insurgency Problem Likely Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dhaka, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is likely
to sign a breakthrough peace agreement soon with the tribal
insurgents in a bid to solve the 23-year-old problem in southern
Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT), official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
However, the sources could not confirm when the agreement would
be signed.
</P>
<P>
"The tribal delegation will fly back today or tomorrow to seek
approval of their partners and before their departure, they are
expected to call on Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina," the sources
added.
</P>
<P>
President of the National Committee on CHT and Chief Whip Abul
Hasanat Abdulla in a written statement Wednesday night said, "We
have agreed to all matters, and an agreement will be signed very
soon." But he did not mention the "matters" they agreed.
</P>
<P>
"The peace talks have ended. This is the last talks in this
regard," He told pressmen, after concluding the four-day crucial
negotiations with the Parbatya Chattagram Jana Sahhati Samiti
(PCJSS), the political wing of the armed tribal rebels.
</P>
<P>
Shantu Larma, head of the PCJSS, endorsed the statement with a
big smile.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the 1970s, the independence-seeking tribal
insurgents have launched a bloody bush war, which cost thousands
of lives, in the 14,200-square-kilometer region, rich in
hydrocarbon deposits and teak.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the PCJSS agreed with the revised
government proposal on the army's role in the Hill Tracts and the
relocation of the Bangalee settlers in the area.
</P>
<P>
It also agreed that the Shanti Bahini, the armed wing of the
PCJSS, would lay down arms while the government had agreed with
the PCJSS's proposals on constitutional recognition of the tribal
people and to give the three hill districts constitutional entity.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is expected to bring about a durable peace in the
CHT and bring back about 50,000 tribal refugees from refugee camps
in the Indian state of Tripura.
</P>
<P>
With the initiative of the present government, over 6,000
refugees have returned to their homeland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
