<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: A New Chapter in Sino-African Friendship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Great changes have taken place in Africa since the end of the
Cold War, changes that did not estrange Africa from China, but, on
the contrary, have enabled them to cooperate more sincerely and
support each other in the international affairs more steadfastly.
</P>
<P>
China and Africa, having no conflict of interest, face the task
to develop economy, share the wide-range common interests in the
international affairs, as well as enjoy a sound basis for
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin put forward a five-point proposal during
his visit to Africa last year -- "to foster a sincere friendship,
to treat each other as equals, to seek common development on the
basis of mutual benefit, to increase consultation and to look into
the future."
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng has also said that "China, which was, is and
will be the friend of Africa, never seeks benefit from Africa and
selflessly provides aid to the continent without any
preconditions. China does not interfere in other country's internal
affairs and respects African peoples' own choices of social
system."
</P>
<P>
While meeting with leaders of Mozambique, Gabon and Cameroon,
Li Peng thanked them for their support on China's human rights
issue. Appreciating the six countries' "one China" policy, Li
stressed that both China and Africa should strengthen cooperation
in the fields of politics and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano remembered that China did
not stop its assistance to his country even when it was in the
greatest difficulty.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Head of State Sani Abacha said that the Sino-African
relations were built on the basis of mutual trust, understanding,
respect and benefit. China is the reliable friend of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li and his wife Zhu Lin also made close contacts with
renowned social figures and women representatives, and visited
many schools and welfare organizations.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the Chinese government and people, they donated
items including sewing machines, computers, medicines, wheel
chairs and stationeries to their African friends.
</P>
<P>
Expressing heart-felt gratitude, the African people said these
items were badly needed in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that with its insistence on the independent
and peaceful diplomacy and the Five Principles of Peaceful
Co-existence, China is enjoying great prestige in the world and in
African people's hearts in a world that is changing rapidly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reuters Starts New Service for Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Reuters, the world news service,
has started a new service to provide on line financial news to
Kenyan users, the "Daily Nation" newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The service, known as Market Watch, will provide up to date
information on foreign exchange rates, commodity markets, share
prices and bond rates at the Nairobi Stock Exchange as well as
stock prices in New York and London.
</P>
<P>
The service uses Internet technology, making it available to
the widest possible audience, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It has specifically been developed for use by corporate
treasurers, finance directors, financial controllers and
subscribers with a keen interest on the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The service was officially launched by Governor of the Central
Bank of Kenya, Micah Cheserem here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Cheserem urged Reuters to maintain
its high standard of reporting financial news and to be balancing
its reports to avoid sensational stories.
</P>
<P>
"The image that has been created that only bad news can be
expected from Africa should be discouraged," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he expects that Reuters, in a good position, can help
educate local and foreign investors on the many opportunities
available in the emerging markets in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Reuters Manager for East Africa Robin Parr said that the new
service has been developed with the eastern African markets in
mind and has incorporated many requests from its existing
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
"We will also be examining the possibility of providing a
communications mechanism with the service so that users can
negotiate and transact deals with the banks quickly, secretly,
securely and efficiently," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
