<HEADLINE> China to Play More Important Role in Asia-Pacific Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Malaysian Foreign Minister
Datuk Abdullah Bin Haji Badawi said today that China will play an
even more important role in the peace and development of
Asia-Pacific region with its rapid economic enhancement.
</P>
<P>
Badawi made the remarks here this morning in a speech at the
forum co-sponsored by the Institute of International Studies, the
China Institute of Contemporary International Relations, and the
Institute of Asia-Pacific Studies of the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Badawi said: "What the Government of China is doing, is in
effect bringing peace, stability, and prosperity to the rest of
the region. It is imperative therefore that the international
community extends its cooperation to China in its economic
reforms. The long-term benefits that can be derived bilaterally,
regionally and internationally with a successful economic reform
in China can hardly be over-emphasised."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the relations between Malaysia and China and
between the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and
China, Badawi pointed out that both Malaysia and China have
repeatedly emphasised that cooperation should be pursued on the
basis of equality and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
Badawi said: "ASEAN appreciates the generally positive momentum
in ASEAN-China relations. The dialogue between the two sides at
both the ministerial and senior officials' level on a wide range
of subjects of importance such as those reflected in the ASEAN
Regional Forum, Asia-Europe Meeting, Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation Organization, and World Trade Organization and
international trade and others have been very encouraging."
</P>
<P>
Badawi said that ASEAN looks forward to celebrating the 30th
anniversary of the founding of ASEAN in August this year, and
Malaysia welcomes that more concrete basis has emerged for
furthering ASEAN-China cooperation and friendship.
</P>
<P>
Badawi stressed that Malaysia and all other ASEAN members have
expressed support for China's entry into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
"We take China as a friend with which we can have a partnership
for peace and prosperity," he said, adding that China's diplomatic
initiatives have generally resulted in a positive development,
regionally and internationally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
