<HEADLINE> Peres: Majority of Israeli People Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The majority of the Israeli
people now agree to the idea of establishing an independent
Palestinian state, said Shimon Peres, opposition leader and former
prime minister, according to the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Peres made the statement when he was addressing a Socialist
International meeting in the West Bank city of Ramallah Wednesday
night. More than 20 members of the organization were present
at the meeting, the first ever held in the Palestinian territory.
</P>
<P>
President of the Palestinian National Authority Yasser Arafat
attended the meeting. Visiting Norwegian Foreign Minister Bjoern
Godal was also present.
</P>
<P>
Peres noted that his conclusion is well founded by a recent
poll, referring to the one conducted by the Tel Aviv-based
prestigious Jafee Center for Strategic Studies.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll, which was released on April 28, 51
percent of the Israelis polled said Israel should agree to the
establishment of a Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip in the context of a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
This shows that the majority of the Israeli people hope to see
that the stalled peace process will resume and go ahead, said
Peres.
</P>
<P>
The Nobel peace prize winner pledged that he will do whatever
he can to push the rightwing Likud government to move along the
road to peace.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party convention, held in Tel Aviv Wednesday,
adopted a platform plank recognizing the Palestinian people's
right to self-determination and for the first time agreeing to
the establishment of an independent Palestinian state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
