<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: A New Chapter in Sino-African Friendship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng wound up on
Wednesday his fruitful official good-will visit to Zambia,
Mozambique, Gabon, Cameroon, Nigeria and Tanzania, and a working
visit to Seychelles.
</P>
<P>
This was Li's fourth visit to Africa, but the first one to
these seven countries.
</P>
<P>
During his stay on the continent from May 3 to 14, Li held
meetings and talks with leaders of the seven nations on a wide
range of topics and reached common understanding with them on many
important issues.
</P>
<P>
It was a trip of peace aimed to deepen mutual understanding and
promote traditional friendship, and a successful trip to seek
mutually beneficial cooperation and common development.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier was warmly greeted by his African hosts who
spoke highly and vividly of the Sino-African relationship.
</P>
<P>
"Zambian-Chinese friendship has stood the test of history, and
the two countries have become 'all-weather friends,'" Zambian
President Frederick Chiluba told Li on May 5 on the first leg of
his official good-will visit.
</P>
<P>
For the Chinese people, the distant African continent is both
familiar and unfamiliar.
</P>
<P>
During the 1950s and 1960s when the tide of independence swept
the poverty-stricken African continent, the Chinese government and
people rendered great support to the Africans in their struggle
for national independence and liberation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people and the African people have since become
true friends standing together through storm and stress, because
they have shared similar experiences, and China's support has
always been sincere.
</P>
<P>
As a Chinese saying goes, "A bosom friend afar brings a distant
land near." Since then, China and Africa have supported each
other, and developing friendship and cooperation with Africa has
become a foundation of China's foreign policy for generations.
</P>
<P>
During the past 30 years, three Chinese presidents and three
premiers have visited some 30 African countries on ten
occasions. They include the late Premier Zhou Enlai's ten-nation
tour between December 1963 and January 1964, and President Jiang
Zemin's visit of six countries in 1996.
</P>
<P>
On their part, more than 100 heads of state and government from
nearly 50 African nations have visited China for about 200 times.
</P>
<P>
Such frequent exchanges of leaders have vigorously propelled
their mutual understanding, trust and cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
