<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Holds Exhibition on Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, May 14 (Xinhua) -- A photo exhibition called Hong
Kong Returns to Motherland was opened today at the National
Archives here.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people attended the opening ceremony which was
inaugurated by Yugoslav Deputy Prime Mimister Nikola Sainovic.
</P>
<P>
Sainovic said that the return of Hong Kong to the motherland is
a great historic event not only significant to Hong Kong and
China, but also to the development of relations between China and
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He also congratulated China on Hong Kong's return and praised
the efforts by the Chinese government, saying "The settlement of
Hong Kong issue proves the correctness of China's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking highly of Deng Xiaoping's concept of "one country, two
systems", Director of Yugoslav National Archives Popovic said that
the first implementation of the concept (return of Hong Kong to
the motherland) in the world is China's first step on its way to
peaceful reunification of the whole country and a good example for
peaceful solution to many international problems and issues left
over from history.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the return of Hong Kong to the motherland
is of immediate concern to not only Hong Kong and China, but also
the Asia-Pacific region and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong creates favorable conditions for
further stability, prosperity and development of this trade and
financial center in the world.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador to Yugoslavia Zhu Ankong said that the
return of Hong Kong to the motherland is an important event in the
modern history of both China and the world. This does not only
mark the end of an old age and the beginning of a new era, but
also a crucial step toward the reunification of China.
</P>
<P>
He believed that Hong Kong will become more prosperous and
stable, which will help promote the economic development and
cooperation in the world.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition of 100 photos shows the history of Hong Kong and
the Chinese people's struggle as well as the Chinese government's
efforts to resume the exercise of sovereignty over the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
