<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Informal Meeting Makes No </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 15 (Xinhua) -- No breakthrough was achieved at
the meeting held overnight between Israeli and Palestinian
officials, which was arranged by U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
The three-way meeting at the residence of U.S. Ambassador
Martin Indyk in Herzliya was attended by Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu's
senior adviser Yitzhak Molcho, and Palestinian senior negotiators
Saeb Erekat and Nabil Shaath.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators sat down together to discuss their differences
since Israel began in late March the controversial Har Homa
construction in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Before the meeting, Erekat hosted Ross in his hometown of
Jericho, where they discussed their positions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Israel Radio after the talks, Erekat said that
although the three-hour meeting was "candid and right to the
point," no clear-cut results were achieved on bridging the wide
gap between the sides.
</P>
<P>
"After the talks, I realize the magnitude of the crisis,"
Erekat said, adding "We are still in a major, major crisis."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side still demanded that Israel freeze the
settlement expansion, including the Har Homa project. Erekat
said there would be no reinstatement of credibility of the peace
process if Israel continued the settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
Erekat viewed the meeting as simply a dialogue instead of
negotiations. He said that the Americans listened to the
opinions of both sides and Ross would take the issues to both
Israeli and Palestinian leaders today.
</P>
<P>
Ross is due to return to Washington Friday after holding
further talks separately with Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat today.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived here last Wednesday on another mediation mission
aimed at breaking the deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks, which have been suspended since Israel began the Har Homa
construction late March.
</P>
<P>
While the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) insists on a
freeze to Israel's settlement expansion as the precondition for
resuming talks, Israel has imposed its own conditions by
demanding the PNA fight terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
