<HEADLINE> South Korean City Bids for 2001 Summer Universiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 15 (Xinhua) -- South Korean city Taegu is bidding for
the 2001 World University Games.
</P>
<P>
The city, famous for its apples and South Korea's textile industry,
expects their bid and host for the games will be a launching pad to
its rise as an international city.
</P>
<P>
Taegu decided to bid for the games in October 1995. After a survey
of the facilities in early 1996, the South Korean government gave a
green light to the city, which was followed by the establishment of
Taegu bidding committee.
</P>
<P>
The Taegu city submitted its application to the International
University Sports Federation (FISU) this month and FISU will decide
the host city before August this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the bidding committee, Taegu will build a 70,140-seat
main stadium, swimming pool, tennis courts, gymnasium and baseball
park for the games if the city was selected as the host.
</P>
<P>
The main stadium, with construction beginning in July, is also
expected to be used as one of the sites for 2002 World Cup soccer
finals. 
