<HEADLINE> Indonesia Plans to Purchase More Hawk Jet Fighters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Bilateral discussions between
Indonesia and Britain for the purchase of 18 more Hawk-100
trainers and Hawk-200 all-weather attack fighters will not be
hampered by the change in the British government, a senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the official handover of eight Hawk-100s and 16
Hawk-200s to the Indonesian air force at the Simpang Tiga airbase
in Riau province on Wednesday, Minister of Defense and Security
Edi Sudradjat said the Hawk fighters are the "most appropriate
choice." "The political change in Britain will not affect our
negotiations for an additional purchase of 18 Hawk-100 and
Hawk-200s," reports reaching here today from Pekanbaru, Riau
province, quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations for the purchase of the British-made jet fighters
started in 1991, while the deal was signed in 1993 with a total
contract of 442.5 million pound sterling.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has also purchased 12 F-16 Falcon fighters from the
United States and several F-5 Tigers, all of which are stationed
in East Java's Madiun and Jakarta's Halim Perdanakusuma airbases.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia plans to buy 12 more F-16s, which the U.S. put up for
sale in 1995.  
