<HEADLINE> Russian-NATO Agreement Binding, Says Yeltsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin said
today that the agreement reached in Moscow Wednesday on
Russian-North Atlantic Treaty Organization relations would be
binding.
</P>
<P>
In a televised interview tonight, Yeltsin said that under the
draft document, NATO could "make decisions only after consensus is
reached through consultations (with Russia).
</P>
<P>
"This is vitally important," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said NATO "will not station nuclear weapons" and use
military facilities left over by the former Warsaw Pact
Organization on the territories of its new members.
</P>
<P>
"Since (the document says) military forces won't be placed on
the territory of new members, then military forces won't be placed
there. Nuclear weapons won't be placed there," Yeltsin told
Russian Television.
</P>
<P>
He said: "As we declared before, we are against the expansion."
</P>
<P>
Russia and NATO had tough negotiations before, as the military
alliance "didn't want to make any commitments," he said. "But in
this document, there are precise commitments."
</P>
<P>
But United States officials said the agreement would create a
formal joint cooperation council and give Russia a voice, not
veto, in NATO decision-making on European security, reports said.
</P>
<P>
And NATO officials said the document contained no pledge about
nuclear forces and merely reaffirmed NATO's statement that it had
"no intention, no reason and no plan" to deploy nuclear weapons in
the territories of new members.
</P>
<P>
On the union treaty between Russia and Belarus, Yeltsin said 80
percent of Russians agreed to have a Russian-Belarussian union.
</P>
<P>
He would examine the draft treaty with Belarussian President
Alexander Lukashenko on May 22 before officially signing it the
following day.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the peace deal signed on Monday with Chechen
rebels, he said the accord "ended 400-year-long disputes between
the two sides." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
