<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Continue Privatizing State Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
continue its policy of privatizing a number of state-owned
companies in order to strengthen their capital structure and
enhance their performance, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"Yet, privatization should not necessarily mean a transfer of
part or all government assets to the private sector. In essence it
comprises all efforts by involving the private sector in the
managing of state companies," Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony for the installation of a new deputy
chief for administration at the State Audit Board, Moerdiono said,
"of the various restructuring possibilities, 'going public' was
the best alternative," officials at the ceremony today quoted the
state secretary as saying.
</P>
<P>
State companies, meanwhile, will continue to play an important
role in running the national economy in the years to come, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Their contributions to the state, among other things, are in
the form of dividends, overall development funds, government share
of the profit as shareholder," Moerdiono noted.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the total amount of the state companies'
contribution to the state for 1995 reached 1.19 trillion rupiah
(500 million U.S. dollars). In addition to this are the income tax
revenues totaling 3.1 trillion rupiah (1.302 billion U.S.
dollars), he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
