<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Province Develops Tropical Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Hainan Province has become China's
biggest grower of tropical agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
On the island province, fruit- and vegetable-growing areas have
risen from 109,000 ha. in 1990 to 237,000 ha. in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The new plantings helped the province bring in nearly 6.9
billion yuan in output value of tropical agricultural products in
1996, compared with nearly 2.4 billion yuan in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 70 percent of the local output of winter fruits and
vegetables are shipped to the mainland. The nearly 500 country
trade fairs scattered throughout the province handled three
billion yuan in trade volume in 1996, a big leap from 768 million
yuan in 1987.
</P>
<P>
The province now boasts 36,000 vehicles for farm use and more
than 6,000 heavy-duty trucks, helping transport the local products
to the market. It also has more than 700 agricultural products
processing enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Hainan has so far attracted 150 million US dollars from
overseas to fund 250 local agricultural projects.
</P>
<P>
Hainan has witnessed an annual 10 percent of growth in local
agricultural output value and five percent of growth in grain
output since 1988, when the island was promoted to be provincial
status. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
