<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fetal Skin Crafts Promise New Clues To Healing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Human fetal skin had been grafted
on to unborn sheep in experiments which may give surgeons new
clues on wound healing, a conference was told today.
</P>
<P>
Plastic surgeon Morris Ritz, of Melbourne's Austin Hospital and
Bernard O'Brien Microsurgery Research Center, has grafted skin
from spontaneously aborted human fetuses on to lambs' skin.
</P>
<P>
The human skin successfully attached to the lamb skin in two
out of four experiments, the Royal Australasian College of
Surgeons annual scientific congress, held in Brisbane, was told.
</P>
<P>
The research aims to provide a new way of studying how wounds
heal in the womb, the Australian Association Press reported.
</P>
<P>
It already is known that in the fetal environment wounds heal
almost "scarlessly" and more quickly than those suffered by humans
outside the womb.
</P>
<P>
The research may also be of benefit in fetal surgery, which is
rarely performed but has been done to save the life of unborn
babies.
</P>
<P>
Dr Ritz said his cross-species grafting technique worked
because the procedure was done early, before the lamb's immune
system had developed to the extent that it would reject the human
skin.
</P>
<P>
The next step would be to deliberately wound the skin and
observe its healing process, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
