<HEADLINE> Peru Arrests Seven Ecuadorean Soldiers on Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Peru announced today that it had
arrested seven Ecuadorean soldiers who were planting mines across
a disputed border.
</P>
<P>
A Peruvian military statement said a heavily armed Ecuadorean
patrol was arrested on Tuesday while planting mines six kilometers
inside Peru's territory. It added that it was only a border
incident and no clashes happened between the two armies.
</P>
<P>
The arrests came as negotiators from Lima and Quito began a
second round of talks in the Brazilian capital, Brasilia, on a
permanent solution to the decades-old border dispute.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador's Defense Ministry issued a communique today saying
seven soldiers were illegally arrested while carrying out normal
activities and routine patrols in the Paquisha Alto sector of the
disputed frontier.
</P>
<P>
The arrested soldiers would be handed over to the Ecuadorean
authorities soon, said Peruvian military sources.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian Congress President Victor Joy Way said the incident
"broke the commitment between the two nations and affects the
peace talks that are underway...(it) disturbs the atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
The two nations had bloody clashes in the border area in
January, 1995, leaving dozens dead and hundreds injured on both
sides. They reached a ceasefire agreement in March, 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
