<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Infected By Chicken Virus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Antarctic penguins have been
infected by the chicken virus, one of the most resistant bird
viruses known to science, posing a potentially massive threat to
the continent's most famous wildlife, Australian researchers
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
No clinical disease was evident in the penguins, further
investigation was warranted, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
Antarctic biologists have long feared the escape of chicken
viruses and have imposed strict regulations on visitors to the
continent including a ban on the consumption of chicken products
outside bases or the disposal of chicken waste.
</P>
<P>
The scientists fear that carelessness may have allowed the
disease, which affects chicks, to be brought to the white
continent by human visitors.
</P>
<P>
The highly contagious Infectious Bursal Disease Virus (INDV) is
known to cause immune deficiency and sometimes death in young
poultry.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government reacted swiftly, announcing a
workshop would look at monitoring program and ways of responding
to possible disease outbreaks.
</P>
<P>
The penguins with the anti-bodies were all found near
Australia's Mawson Station.
</P>
<P>
Dr Heather Gardner with the Australian Antarctic Division, one
of the researchers involved in the study, said up to 65 percent of
emperor penguin chicks studied had virus anti-bodies.
</P>
<P>
The researchers tested 53 emperor penguin chicks and 133 adult
Adelie penguins at three sites 40 km to 60 km from Mawson between
December 1995 and February last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
