<HEADLINE> ECO to Further Develop Regional Transportation, Telecom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 14 (Xinhua) -- A high-level meeting of the Economic
Cooperation Organization (ECO) ended today in Ashkhabad, capital
of Turkmenistan, deciding to develop regional transportation and
telecommunications infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
A joint declaration issued by leaders of the ten ECO member
states said the ECO will also develop a transnational oil and gas
pipelines network, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The document said the ECO members would link up their trunk
roads and railways, and speed up the writing of accords on transit
transportation and the implementation of transit trade as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ten countries would establish industrial groups
for the purpose of building transnational oil and gas pipelines.
</P>
<P>
Reports said during the meeting, presidents of Turkmenistan,
Iran and Turkey also signed a memorandum on building a
Turkmenistan-Europe natural gas transport pipeline.
</P>
<P>
A senior ECO official said at the closing ceremony that the
meeting has opened a new era for regional economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The ECO was established in 1985 by Iran, Pakistan and Turkey,
and later joined by Azerbaijan, Afghanistan, Turkmenistan,
Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
