<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hard Day for Thailand's Foreign Exchange, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's foreign exchange and
stock markets were dealt further blows when speculation endangered
the Thai currency.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's speculative attack on the baht was in part blamed
on reports concerning Deputy Prime Minister and concurrently
Finance Minister Amnuay Virawan possibly being forced to leave the
government to take responsibility for failing to revive the Thai
economy.
</P>
<P>
The official mid-rate of the Thai currency, baht, was fixed at
25.86 baht to the US dollar on Wednesday, but the market rate,
spurred by heavy speculation about a possible devaluation of the
baht and the possible resignation of Finance Minister Amnuay
Virawan, soared to as high as 26.35 baht, 49 satangs higher than
the mid rate.
</P>
<P>
Theoretically, the Thai central bank allows only a four-satang
trading bandwidth, two satangs above or below the mid-rate.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, the Bank of Thailand joined hands with the
Monetary Authority of Singapore to fend off a heavy speculative
attack on the baht.
</P>
<P>
The intervention reportedly took place in the afternoon,
following the baht fell to its lowest level against the dollar in
more than 11 years.
</P>
<P>
The joint intervention helped the baht to rebound to
26.11-26.14 baht per dollar, according to dealers.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the heavy decline in the baht's value provided an
unwelcome challenge to Thailand's coalition government to show its
ability to revive the economy.
</P>
<P>
Confidence in the Thai economy has been battered over the past
two years by a slowdown in export growth, the massive current
account deficit and slumps in both the stock and property markets.
</P>
<P>
On the stock exchange market, the Stock Exchange of Thailand
(SET) index tumbled 4.82 percent, or 28.94 points, on Wednesday to
close at 571.30, the lowest level since the end of 1991.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark index has lost 260.27 points, or 31.3 percent,
since the beginning of this year, and almost 60 percent in two
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0263 </DOCNO>
