<HEADLINE> Upper Mekong Cooperation Moves Closer to Reality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Economic cooperation among upper
Mekong countries has moved a step closer to reality with progress
on two roads linking Thailand with Laos and South China, Poj
Indhuwongse, Thai Consul-General in Kunming, told a seminar here.
</P>
<P>
The seminar on economic cooperation among Myanmar, Laos,
Thailand and China's Yunnan province, organized by the Chinese
Studies Center at Chulalongkorn University, is taking place
Wednesday and today.
</P>
<P>
The two roads Poj was referring to were a 250-kilometer road
from Thailand's Chiang Rai via Huay Sai and Luang Namtha in Laos
to Xishuanbanna in China's Yunnan province and a 260-kilometer
route linking Huay Kon in Thailand's Nan province with the
Laotian-Chinese border.
</P>
<P>
Poj expects both roads to be completed within the next three
years allowing Thailand to tap natural resources in Yunnan, and
enabling China to use Thailand's Laem Chabang Port as an outlet
for its exports. Laos will collect toll fares from both countries.
</P>
<P>
"The development of the economic quadrangle will happen once
transportation routes are developed," he said.
</P>
<P>
Work on both roads began with the resolution of initial funding
problems. The Thai Surathip Group agreed to finance the first
route, which is being developed by a Thai mining company as part
of a joint venture with other Thai businessmen and the Laotian
government.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government agreed to help secure funds for the
Laotian section of the second road, which is also supported by the
Chamber of Commerce of Thailand's Nan province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
