<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The second International Forum on
"Old Age, Aging and the Community" opened here today, and will
discuss a number of important topics in its interdisciplinary
program of old age studies.
</P>
<P>
This program, established in 1995, has organized national and
international conferences, published books and offered
postgraduate courses, extension conferences and advised public and
private institutions about specific activities for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
Marta Larraechea, the First Lady of Chile, inaugurated the
three-day event which was attended by health officials including
senior people from the United States'.
</P>
<P>
In her speech, Larraechea emphasized: "These sessions are the
expression of a challenge we have as a country. We must reflect
deeply about how we are inserting the elderly in our societies."
</P>
<P>
The Chilean government has been paying much attention to the
old. This year Chile will grant a winter bonus of about 53 dollars
to around 600,000 senior citizens for the second time.
</P>
<P>
To date, there are 1.3 million people in Chile over the age of
65 which represents 9.9 percent of the total population. It was
expected that the population of over 65-year-olds will account for
16 percent of the total by the year 2005. 
