<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Children Play Special Role in China's IDD Control Drive (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Using iodized salt is the easiest, cheapest, and the most
effective method to curb IDD," says Hou Peisen.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, many people haven't used it out of
ignorance. Some are still lured by cheaper but unauthorized
iodine-free salt, and many others are using iodined salt
incorrectly," he notes.
</P>
<P>
IDD has emerged as a serious public health problem of China in
recent decades since about 40 percent of people who live in IDD
areas in the world are living in China, in almost every province,
municipality, and autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
"The worst thing is that about six million babies are born in
the IDD areas every year," Hou says, adding that IDD can seriously
affect development of fetus' brain and eventually do harm to human
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
"IDD prevention is vital to improving the general quality of
our children and the younger generation, and it is vital to our
country's development in the next century," says teacher Wang.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng committed the country to eliminating
IDD by the year 2000 when he signed the "World Declaration for the
Survival, Protection, and Development of Children" on March, 1991.
</P>
<P>
To fulfill the goal, the Chinese government has tightened
controls over the salt-making sector to ensure iodized salt is
distributed to every corner of the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the State Education Commission (SEC) is planning to
intensify health education among primary and middle school
students, as at Yumin Primary School, according to Liao Wenke,
chief of Hygiene and Health Education Division of SEC.
</P>
<P>
"More children and their parents will gain knowledge of IDD
control as we conduct a nationwide inspection to promote health
education this year," Liao tells Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"Backed by successful health education among Chinese people and
other measures, China will surely eliminate IDD as scheduled," Hou
Peisen says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
