<HEADLINE> Indonesia Still Faces Japan's Request at WTO Panel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Japan has not withdrawn its request
for a World Trade Organization (WTO) panel meeting on the
Indonesian national car policy, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"I really do not know what would happen on May 23, 1997,
because Japan has not withdrawn its request," Minister of Industry
and Trade Tunky Ariwibowo said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Japan has been delaying the panel meeting scheduled for May 23,
1997, Antara news agency today quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Japanese press reported that Japan postponed the panel meeting
on the consideration that Indonesia was busy with its general
election.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Japan officially forwarded the car dispute to
the WTO dispute settlement board. Japan was complaining
Indonesia's national car policy which gives import and luxury tax
exemptions to a domestic car maker.
</P>
<P>
Japan, the United States and the European Union (EU) have held
a series of bilateral talks with Indonesia after lodging a
complaint with the WTO in October last year in an attempt to get
Jakarta to remove measures which the trio claim are discriminatory
and against multilateral trade rules.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to reports, the EU will next week ask WTO
members to set up a panel to look into Indonesia's national car
policy.
</P>
<P>
The United States has also been in consultations with Indonesia
over the policy, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government announced its national car policy in
February last year, under the policy, domestic car makers can
enjoy tax exemption on condition they raise the local content
ratios in their cars up to 60 percent in three years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
