<HEADLINE> Nepal, Bhutan to Resume Refugee Talks Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Nepal and Bhutan have agreed to
resume bilateral talks soon in order to solve the lingering
problem of Bhutanese refugees in East Nepal, press reports here
said today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a Tuesday evening meeting between
Nepali Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand and Bhutanese King
Jigme Singhe Wangchuck in Maldives, where they were attending a
South Asian regional summit.
</P>
<P>
According to an official of the Nepali Foreign Ministry, the
two leaders had "useful talks in a cordial atmosphere" and had
realized the need to come to an early solution to the refugee
problem.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100,000 Bhutanese, mostly of Nepalese origin, have been
living in eight refugee camps in eastern Nepal since 1990 when
they were forced to fled to Nepal under Bhutan's "One Nation, One
People" policy, causing severe social and employment headache for
the Nepali government.
</P>
<P>
The earlier seven rounds of bilateral talks at ministerial
level between the two Himalayan kingdoms made no progress in the
settlement of the controversial issue as Bhutan insisted that some
of the refugees were not genuine Bhutanese citizens.  
</P>
</TEXT>
