<HEADLINE> Brazil: Cautious on Forming Free Trade Bloc in America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELO HORIZONTE, Brazil, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Brazil today called
for a cautious approach toward setting up the Free Trade Area of
the Americas (FTAA) by 2005, saying the American countries should
eliminate trade barriers between them before negotiating tariff
cuts.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Third Business Forum of the Americas, Brazilian
Industry and Commerce Minister Francisco Dornelles said the
creation of the bloc cannot be speeded up because countries such
as Brazil need time to choose "a more propitious moment in the
implementation of market liberalization."
</P>
<P>
The idea contradicted the stance of the United States and
Canada, which wanted to start negotiations on all aspects of trade
liberalization at the same time, including tariff cuts.
</P>
<P>
But Dornelles acknowledged that the FTAA is an ideal that
should be pursued with the utmost effort. "Continental trade has
enormous potential for growth, as we move towards the process of
free trade," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the building of the FTAA can only be achieved with
the full participation of the business circle in the 34 countries
of America.
</P>
<P>
The forum was held parallel to the third meeting of the trade
ministers to decide the timetable for negotiations on setting up
the FTAA by 2002, which was agreed in 1994 by all the American
countries but Cuba at the Miami summit.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 businessmen from across the Americas gathered to
discuss the future trade bloc, which would represent over half of
the world trade and counterweigh the European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
