<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Children Play Special Role in China's IDD Control Drive (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Mu Tong is a first-grade pupil at
Yumin Primary in Beijing, but sometimes he acts like a teacher in
the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
"You can't put salt in the pot so early!" "Please remember to
put the lid on the salt jar after you use it!" the seven-year-old
Mu Tong instructs his mother while she is stir-frying dishes.
</P>
<P>
His "teachings" on how to use salt for cooking are in fact
learned from school.
</P>
<P>
"My teachers often tell us that iodine in salt would volatilize
if you put salt in cooking pot too early or leave the salt jar
open," the boy says.
</P>
<P>
What he learns is part of a program about Iodine Deficiency
Disorders (IDD) prevention, which Chinese health and educational
departments are making efforts to make hundreds of millions of
Chinese youngsters know.
</P>
<P>
"We feel it urgent to spread the knowledge across the country
because the health of many Chinese people is endangered by the
disease while they are unaware of it," says Hou Peisen, an
official of the National Office of Endemic Diseases Control under
the Ministry of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
Hou pointed out what Mu Tong's school does in this field has
set a successful example in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We started to spread IDD prevention knowledge among students
in 1993. We encouraged them to remind their family members to use
iodized salt correctly," says Wang Xiuqin, 53, a teacher of
Chinese language in Yumin Primary School.
</P>
<P>
Helped by medical experts, they edited a pamphlet about IDD
prevention and presented many volumes to a village primary school
in north China's Chengde City, a mountainous area with a high
incidence of IDD.
</P>
<P>
The students also published an article in "China Children's
News", a national daily with a vast circulation among teenagers,
calling on their counterparts to promote the use of iodized salt,
according to the teacher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Minor Eruptions Reported at Mexico's Popocatepetl Volcano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The Popocatepetl volcano, 65
kilometers northeast of this Mexican capital, have erupted twice
in the past 24 hours, the National Disaster Prevention Center said.
</P>
<P>
The minor eruptions, which apparently have caused no human
injuries, occurred at 10:29 p.m. local time Tuesday and 00:40
a.m. today respectively and shot ash and rocks into the air.
</P>
<P>
They followed several latest similar eruptions taking place on
Sunday at the 5,452-meter-high volcano, which had been dormant
since 1720 but turned active in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
As explosions caused by the latest eruptions shook doors and
windows of the houses near the volcano, villagers have expressed
their concern about a future eruption.
</P>
<P>
The authorities said an alert remains effective for local
communities while state Interior Ministry personnel are visiting
the area to help those in need.
</P>
<P>
Seven million pesos (about 897,000 U.S. dollars) have been
allotted in the past two years to help secure the safety of people
living close to Popocatepetl.
</P>
<P>
The government has repaired roads and bridges, and delivered
signs indicating the routes to be followed in the event of
evacuation.
</P>
<P>
More than 10 villages have been provided with cellular phones
and have had 2,393 vehicles at their disposition for emergency
uses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
