<HEADLINE> Magic Wants Jackson for Team Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The Orlando Magic have offered
Chicago Bulls' coach Phil Jackson a five-year, 30 million
U.S. dollars coaching contract, reports reaching here said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jackson will complete his one-year, 2.75 million U.S. dollars
deal with the Bulls by the end of this playoffs.
</P>
<P>
The Magic has reportedly wooed Jackson through his agent, Todd
Musburger, for several weeks. The club would not comment on the
offer.
</P>
<P>
The Magic also are looking at former Detroit Pistons coach
Chuck Daly, who reportedly spoke with team officials last
weekend. Daly, 66, led the Pistons to the NBA title in 1989 and
1990 but has not coached since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Orlando fired coach Brian Hill in mid-season and named
assistant Richie Adubato as his interim replacement. The Magic
finished 45-37 and lost to the Miami Heat in the first round of
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
Chicago star Michael Jordan has said he would not return to the
Bulls without Jackson as coach. Several Chicago players said they
would not be surprised if Jackson sought another job.
</P>
<P>
Jackson hopes to guide the Bulls to their fifth title in seven
years. Only two other coaches in NBA history have surpassed his
title total. Jackson has a career record of 483-173 in his eight
seasons as Bulls coach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
