<P>
Dini pledged his country's continued support to making the
agreement fully operational so that it can be used to build a new
and more solid European security architecture, in view of future
NATO enlargement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, announced today in Moscow after two days' tough
negotiations, is to be officially signed on May 27, after gaining
approvals from the 16 NATO members and Russian President Boris
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Italian Foreign Ministry said that in the coming
talks between Dini and his Russian counterpart in Moscow next
week, NATO-Russia relation will be on top of the agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
