<HEADLINE> Honduras, El Salvador End Demarcation of Border Section </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Honduras and El Salvador have
concluded the demarcation of the third section of their common
border under the General Peace Treaty signed in 1980.
</P>
<P>
To date, the two neighboring Central American countries have
marked off 130 kilometers of their 374.5 kilometers common border,
the Honduran Foreign Ministry announced today.
</P>
<P>
Under a ruling handed down by the International Court of
Justice in the Hague, the Netherlands, the two countries still
have 244.5 kilometers of border to be demarcated.
</P>
<P>
Oscar Villagran, chairman of El Salvador's border demarcation
committee, is here meeting his Honduran counterpart Raul Andino.
</P>
<P>
He said today both sides would speed up the demarcation process
in the sectors of the Ex-Bolsones Nahuaterique and Dolores, where
there have been serious disputes over sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Andino said Honduras was interested in getting the
work done as soon as possible although the new topography in the
Ex-Bolsones prolonged the time needed for demarcation.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are scheduled to finish establishing limits
and marking off a 97-kilometer border section by the end of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
