<HEADLINE> Costa Rica's Inflation Over 5 Percent in January-April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica accumulated 5.21
percent of inflation in the first four months of this year, the
Economy Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The Consumer Price Index moved up 1.34 percent in April, the
second biggest monthly advance so far of the year, after January's
2.06 percent, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The transportation sector, which reported an average price hike
of five percent, was the one with the highest inflation.
</P>
<P>
Jose Leon Desanti, minister of economy, said inflation for the
year will not exceed 12 percent, namely the goal set by the
government in its commitments to international financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Desanti emphasized that the arrival of new foreign investment,
more credit and lower interest rates are factors likely to
contribute to the revival of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica's economy contracted last year and has been in
depression since 1995.
</P>
<P>
While the government hopes the Central American country's
economy could grow by more than 2.5 percent this year, independent
economists see the possibility of a smaller increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
