<HEADLINE> Vietnam Sentences Eight Drug Traffickers to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The Hanoi People's Court sentenced
eight people to death and 14 others to imprisonment in the
country's biggest drug trial on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 22 suspects were found guilty of involvement in a
trafficking ring, which is said to have brought several hundred
kilograms of heroin into Vietnam since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Two policemen, including a former captain of the Interior
Ministry's anti-drug unit, and a border officer were among the
eight sentenced to death by the court.
</P>
<P>
Of those being sent to prison, eight were given life terms,
while the others were given jail terms of between one and 20
years, said a court source.
</P>
<P>
The case erupted following the arrest and conviction of a
Laotian drug trafficker, who broke down in 1996 shortly before he
was due to be executed and offered to exchange information on the
syndicate in exchange for leniency.
</P>
<P>
Under Vietnam's law, people sentenced to death are given a
15-day appeal period. If the appeal fails, their ultimate hopes
lie with a presidential pardon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
