<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (83-84) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the Basic
Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (83-84) in a
question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Will various religious activities and missionary
schools continue after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: The Basic Law stipulates, "Hong Kong residents shall
have freedom of religious belief and freedom to preach and to
conduct and participate religious activities in public."
</P>
<P>
It also stipulates, "The Government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region shall not restrict the freedom of religious
belief, interfere in the internal affairs of religious
organizations or restrict religious activities which do not
contravene the laws of the Region. Religious organizations shall,
in accordance with law, enjoy the right to acquire, use, dispose
of and inherit property, and the right to receive financial
assistance."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, religious undertakings will continue to exist and
develop in Hong Kong after 1997.
</P>
<P>
Schools run by religious organizations account for a large
proportion of those operated by social bodies.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law stipulates that religious organizations may,
according to their previous practice, continue to run seminaries
and other schools. Schools run by religious organizations may
continue to provide religious education including religious
courses.
</P>
<P>
Question: Will religious organizations be permitted to maintain
ties with foreign religious organizations after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Owing to historical reasons, religious organizations in
Hong Kong have maintained fairly extensive and close ties with
various countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Out of respect for this fact, Article 141 of the Basic Law
stipulates, "Religious organizations and believers in the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region may maintain and develop their
relations with religious organizations and believers elsewhere."
</P>
<P>
Article 149 of the Basic Law also stipulates that religious
organizations in the Hong Kong SAR may maintain and develop
relations with their counterparts in foreign countries and regions
and with relevant international organizations. They may, as
required, use the name "Hong Kong, China" in relevant activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anhui Boy Survives with Taiwan Donated Marrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 15 (Xinhua) -- A 17-year-old boy from east China's
Chuzhou City, Anhui Province has survived leukaemia after a
transplant of marrow donated by a middle-aged Taiwan women.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily reported that the first cross-Straits
cooperation in marrow transplant was between Beijing Beitaipinglu
Hospital under the People's Liberation Army in western part of
Beijing and a marrow bank in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan woman, whose family name is Zhang, volunteered to
donate marrow for the mainland youngster after hearing the news
that the Marrow Donation Data Center in Taiwan began its search
for a donor with Liu's type of marrow.
</P>
<P>
Chen Hu, deputy director of the blood disease department of the
Beijing Beitaipinglu Hospital said the health of the boy keeps
improving and he is also under close observation by doctors in his
hospital.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jinquan's white cell count has grown from 0 to 4,400 per
cubic millimeter and the level for a healthy person is about 2,500
each cubic millimeter, said Chen, who successfully searched for
the marrow for the boy.
</P>
<P>
Liu was diagnosed with chronic granulocyte leukaemia last
August. So far, the usual cure for the disease is marrow
transplant and most of the patients underwent the surgery with
marrow offered by their family members or relatives.
</P>
<P>
As the only child in the family, Liu had to find a donor from
outside his family.
</P>
<P>
The most important step for transplant is to find the right
type of marrow. However, the odds are only one in 300,000 people.
</P>
<P>
His father had brought the boy to many big hospitals in
Shanghai, Guangzhou and Beijing, but nothing could be done due to
a lack of marrow.
</P>
<P>
The Red Cross Society of China began to promote donations of
marrow several years ago, but only 3,000 people responded.
</P>
<P>
The father and son went to see Chen after watching a Central
Chinese Television Station program that aired news about Chen Hu's
seeking of marrow for another child with leukaemia through the
Marrow Bank of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that Marrow Bank of Taiwan has registered more than
140,000 voluntary donors.
</P>
<P>
Chen examined Liu and then passed on the information to the
Marrow Bank in Taiwan. The bank began a five-month search for a
donor with Liu's type of marrow before finding Mrs. Zhang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Defense Chief Announces Task Force to Reform Pentagon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen today announced the formation of a task force to reform the
Pentagon for more savings.
</P>
<P>
Cohen named a panel of current and former defense officials and
outside experts to advise him on how to downsize his own office
and the military service.
</P>
<P>
"There's a great deal of redundancy in much of what we do. And
essentially, it has been growing like topsy, and we have to find
ways in which we can achieve savings," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The panel, headed by Pentagon Comptroller John Hamre, will help
the defense chief analyze Pentagon's business practices and
make suggestions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said he quickly discovered there was not enough time to
assess how the Pentagon could reduce its own bureaucracy and he
needed more time for such a review.
</P>
<P>
The United States has some 1.45 million members of the active
duty military, 813,000 civilians who work for the military
departments and the Office of the Secretary of Defense, and
another 566,000 "blue collar" support staff.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said he had no specific targets in mind for the size or
type of cuts he might propose, noting that some may require
congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Quadrennial Defense Report, originally
scheduled for Thursday, would be made public on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The project reportedly would leave the existing military force
and military strategy largely intact, with the basic U.S. goal of
being able to fight two major regional wars simultaneously.
</P>
</TEXT>
