<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business In China's Five SEZs Booming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, May 15 (Xinhua) -- The role of China's special economic
zones as pilots in the opening up process was highlighted as the
four cities and one province attracted 6.85 billion US dollars in
overseas investment last year.
</P>
<P>
The zones, namely Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Shantou, Xiamen, and Hainan
were the first to benefit from China's reform and opening-up
policy of the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
In Shenzhen and Zhuhai, in Guangdong province, overseas
investment increased by over 33 percent last year, and 100
overseas-funded enterprises in Xiamen, in Fujian province. Such
investment has also added 347 million US dollars worth of capital
to the assets in Xiamen in 1996, accounting for 21 percent of
overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March this year, Xiamen had approved 1,391
Taiwan-funded projects, with nearly three billion US dollars of
contractual investment, and 40 percent of its industrial output
comes from those enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
