<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Following are major news items in
leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard ruled out yesterday further
spending cuts in the 1998 budget and left open the option of
increasing the 450 Australian dollar (351 US dollar) tax rebate on
savings in the lead-up to the next election.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- A leading Australian expert on savings believes the
government's new tax rebate on savings may have a negative impact
on national savings. While it should encourage more private
savings, this was unlikely to offset the scheme's 2 billion
Australian dollar (1.56 billion US dollar) cost.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Auditor-General Ches Baragwanath yesterday urged coalition
MPs to abandon party politics and vote against the government to
protect his office. He warned that changes to his office proposed
by the government, which would strip him of his power to directly
audit the public sector, could render parliament impotent to fight
oppression and corruption by any future government.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- The budget's proposed crackdown on trading in franking
credits sent tremors through the financial services industry
yesterday. The worst-affected area of the market was trading of
options and other derivatives, which slumped as investors
attempted to assess the different role these products will have
under the new tax regime. 
</P>
