<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Beats Sweden to Win World Champion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Canada edged Olympic Sweden 2-1
and sealed a 2-1 final series victory to take its 21st world title
in the ice hockey world championship on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The victory capped a gritty comeback by the Canadians after
they had lost the first game of the best-of-three final on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Dean Evason, the only non-NHL player on the Canadian roster,
netted the only goal of the first period when he hammered home a
loose puck from the side of the Sweden net after goaltender Tommy
Salo failed to control the rebound from a shot by Owen Nolan.
</P>
<P>
Nolan added the second early in the second period when Travis
Green threaded a perfect pass through a crowd in the slot.
</P>
<P>
Michael Nylander scored a third-period reply for the Swedes.
</P>
<P>
"We knew we were going to win and they were hoping," said
Canadian coach Andy Murray.
</P>
<P>
"I told our players just before the game that right now the
Swedes are sitting in their dressing room hoping we're going to
play a bad game, hoping that Sean Burke's going to have a bad day,
that Owen Nolan isn't going to score."
</P>
<P>
The win ended a frustrating string of second-place finishes for
Canada that stretched back to the 1994 Olympics, won by Sweden in
an overtime shootout.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
