<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Parliament Bars Sinn Fein From Opening Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 14 (Xinhua) -- British parliament today barred two
members of Sinn Fein, who were also newly-elected MPs, from
opening an office in parliament.
</P>
<P>
House of Commons Speaker Betty Boothroyd said Sinn Fein party
leader Gerry Adams and chief negotiator Martin McGuinness could
only use the facilities of parliament if they were prepared to be
sworn in as members, according to local reports.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein is the political wing of the Irish Republican Army
which has been fighting to end the British rule in Northern
Ireland and merge the province with the Irish republic.
</P>
<P>
Adams and McGuinness were elected parliament members in the May
1 election. They refused to take the oath of allegiance to Queen
Elizabeth but planned to maintain a parliamentary office.
</P>
<P>
Boothroyd said those who choose not to take their seats should
not have access to the many benefits and facilities now available
in this House without also taking up their responsibilities as
members.
</P>
<P>
Adams said he was not surprised by the parliament decision but
would give "a commitment to our electorate that we would not give
a nod to an English queen."
</P>
<P>
He said both he and McGuinness would be going to the British
parliament "to pick up our passes, look around the place and do a
little press work."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Sinn Fein said it would consider legal action if Adams
and McGuinness were banned from using House of Commons facilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970515.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CBI Responds to Queen's Speech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The Confederation of British
Industry (CBI) today gave a favorable response to the Labor
gvernment's legislative proposals outlined in the Queen's speech.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the proposals, Adair Turner, director-general of
the CBI, said, "This is a very full program from a government
obviously keen to put into action many of its manifesto
proposals."
</P>
<P>
"It is vital that in doing so the government listens to the
views of everyone affected, so it was particularly pleasing to
hear that a positive partnership with business will be at the
heart of the government's plans," added Turner.
</P>
<P>
The CBI also welcomed the government's commitment to raising
education standards and to promoting lifelong learning in the
workplace, and its emphasis on achieving high and stable levels of
economic growth and employment.
</P>
<P>
The commitment to playing a positive role in the European Union
is one which business can strongly support, the CBI stressed.
</P>
<P>
However, the CBI said, concerns remain over plans for the
windfall tax on privatized utilities, and over the details of a
national minimum wage (NMW).
</P>
<P>
Referring to NMW, the CBI stated that it "has not been
convinced that NMW is the best way to tackle poverty, it accepts
that the government has a mandate for its introduction."
</P>
<P>
"The CBI will seek to play a constructive role in the proposed
Low Pay Commission, to ensure that the implementation of the NMW
is sensitive to the needs of the labor market and the concerns of
business," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
