<HEADLINE> US Dollar Plunges Toward 117 yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar slid to another
four-month low against the yen today and fell in most other
dealings after benign inflation data raised doubts that the
Federal Reserve will lift interest rates next week.
</P>
<P>
It was the eighth straight day that the dollar fell against the
yen and left the U.S. currency 8.1 percent below its 4.5 years
intraday high of 127.47 yen set only two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the dollar settled at 117.20 yen, down from 118.50
yen Tuesday and the lowest level since January 17. The latest
decline left the dollar barely 1 percent higher than its 1996
close of 115.93 yen.
</P>
<P>
The dollar cost 1.6944 marks in New York, down from 1.6959
Tuesday and off 2.5 percent from its 38-month high of 1.7386 marks
set on May 5. But the dollar is still 10 percent higher against
the mark compared with the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The pound rallied to 1.6466 U.S. dollars, up from 1.6329 U.S.
dollars, partly on trader expectations that interest rates in
Britain will rise further.
</P>
<P>
The dollar weakness intensified in U.S. trading on the decline
in April wholesale prices, the largest drop in nearly four years
and the fourth straight decrease.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday:
1.4363 Swiss francs, down from 1.4373; 5.7055 French francs, up
from 5.7045; 1,669.00 Italian lire, down from 1,676.00; 1.3889
Canadian dollars, up from 1.3868. 
</P>
</TEXT>
