<HEADLINE> US Disappointed Over Failure of Zaire Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States expressed its
disappointment today over the failure of scheduled talks between
Zairian President Mobutu Sese Seko and rebel leader Laurent
Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Kabila refused to board a South African ship in
the Congolese port of Pointe Noire. He insisted the talks should
take place in international waters, a demand rejected by South
African President Nelson Mandela, who was to have chaired the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to Kabila's refusal, U.S. State Department spokesman
Nicholas Burns said that the United States was "very disappointed
that the talks did not take place" Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We thought the talks were necessary to establish the
conditions for an effective transition," he said.
</P>
<P>
Burns urged Mobutu and Kabila to arrange another direct talks
and hoped that dispute over the venue could be solved.
</P>
<P>
"We would encourage Mr Kabila and President Mobutu to find a
way to speak to each other directly, or else we fear for future
events ... if there's not an agreement to work out a peaceful
transition," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
