<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Kills 8 in Home for Retarded, Elderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 14 (Xinhua) -- A fire engulfed a home for the
mentally retarded and elderly, in Harveys Lake, Pennsylvania,
killing eight people, authorities said today.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters worked through the early morning hours to put out
the blaze at Country Manor Personal Care, a two-story home for 21
residents aged between the mid-40s to late 90s, said Harveys Lake
Fire Chief Frank Lutinski. At least seven residents were
hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
Emergency workers returned this morning to scour the gutted
hulk for bodies and to search for the cause of the worst fire this
town of 2,700 has seen in 40 years, the Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
By mid-afternoon, they had accounted for eight victims while
one more person remained unaccounted for but was presumed dead,
Mayor Richard Boice said today.
</P>
<P>
With help from the home's staff, several escaped the burning
building shortly after the fire started around 9 p.m. Tuesday.
Firefighters pulled other people out of windows, Lutinski said,
but the flames and heat stymied the rescue effort.
</P>
<P>
Social service agencies dealing with the mentally retarded
placed most of the residents in the home, according to Jim Durso
of the Wyoming Valley Red Cross. State officials said others were
elderly who needed some help getting around.
</P>
<P>
Some Country Manor residents were bedridden, but most took care
of themselves with some help from medical staff, Lutinski said.
The home is categorized as a "personal care" home, which serves
people not badly disabled enough to need a full-service nursing
home.
</P>
<P>
The seven people admitted to hospitals included two who were
transferred to the burn center at the Lehigh Valley Medical Center
in Allentown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
