<HEADLINE> S&AMP;P Raises Foreign Currency Credit Rating of Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 14 (Xinhua) -- The Standard &AMP; Poor's, the New
York-based world's leading rating company, today has raised its
foreign currency credit rating on Hong Kong to `A'-Plus from `A'
and its local currency credit rating on Hong Kong to `AA'-minus
from `A'-plus.
</P>
<P>
"The outlook is revised to stable from positive," according to
a report issued by the company today.
</P>
<P>
The company said that the upgrade is based on the improvement
in ratings of the Chinese mainland, whose incentives to respect
Hong Kong's autonomy will continue to be strong.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's new ratings also reflect the government's very
strong creditor position, with very low debt, and fiscal reserves
amounting to 12 percent of the gross domestic product this year,
it said. The government's assets of the future special
administrative region are to rise to 26 percent of GDP in 1998,
according to the company.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Hong Kong continues showing a wealthy
and dynamic economy. Its per capita income has reached about
26,000 U.S. dollars, by far the highest of any rated regions in
the single-`A' category. Its GDP growth has averaged more than 5
percent annually in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the H.K. dollar credit rating balances a
stronger capacity to service local currency debt, due to the
government's taxation powers and control of the domestic
financial system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
