<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Bright Prospects in Asia-Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 14 (Xinhua) -- Asia and the Pacific will
maintain the momentum of intensified participation in the
globalization and regionalization processes in coming years,
according to a survey prepared by the UN Economic and Social
Council.
</P>
<P>
The survey of economic and social conditions in Asia and the
Pacific, 1997, estimated that the export volume of South Asia will
increase by 7.3 percent annually over the period 1996-2005 and
that of East and South-East Asia by 10.1 percent, much higher than
the 6.3 percent annual increase worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The prospects for private financial flows appear favorable.
With moderate international interest rates and continued fiscal
consolidation in industrial countries, the consequential pressures
to diversify portfolios will favor the region because of its
higher growth prospects and the expected continuation of
liberalization and deregulation of financial sector policy
regimes.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investment will continue to be promoted by the
per capita incomes in developing countries of the region, which
are rising at higher rates than in the rest of the developing
world, and increasing competition in the industrial countries and
the resultant pressures on their transnational firms to locate
abroad in search of reduced production cost.
</P>
<P>
The regional cooperation in trade and investment will be
sustained and gather stronger momentum due to rising per capita
consumption, overall export growth, moderate inflation and modest
current account deficits.
</P>
<P>
The survey also noted the huge market potential in the region,
which extends to 37 percent of the world's land area and contains
62 percent of the world's population. The population with an
annual per capita income of over 10,000 dollars numbers more than
a billion in the region, far exceeding the total population of all
the developed countries, according to the survey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
